This handsome hunk is Chance! He is about 9 months old and weighs about 50 lbs. He is as sweet as they come and is just a giant goofball. He loves every person he meets, is submissive with other dogs, LOVES to play and run and is just an all around sweetheart. He does really well in a home with other dogs and for his happiness, he will need to be placed in a home with some buddies to love and play with. He could use some manners as he is learning not to jump on people but does it out of complete love.:-) He would be a great running, hiking, or adventure buddy and would love to explore the mountains of CO with his new family. This is one special boy and we can't wait to find him the home he truly deserves. 

Chance is located in a foster home in Denver, Co.. He is neutered, up to date on all shots, microchipped and his adoption fee is $250. If you would like to add this cutie to your family, please complete an application here-

https://www.tracyspawsrescue.org/adoption-application

****PENDING ADOPTION ***

If you love decadent, delicious, and delightful desserts, then MatchDog has your dish! Welcome the Cutie Pie Pups - chock full of fluffy morsels to tempt your sweet tooth! Indulge today!

Meet beautiful Natalie! A 1-2-year-old female Lab blend WEIGHING 41.5 POUNDS, she is fully grown and ready to take on the world! Natalie was an owner surrender (her family couldn't take care of her due to financial reasons). She was going to be placed in a shelter but our foster friends were able to convince her owners to allow MatchDog to take her. Now, this sweet, sweet girl is under our care. Natalie's foster says that she is calm, loving and friendly. Playful, too! She'll need a family that loves to go for walks and jogs or one that will be able to provide a yard in which she can run and have fun. Crate trained and house trained, she'll be ready for her new home in February. If you are looking for a new buddy to take on 2021 with, Natalie's your gal! Don't delay! Apply for this fabulous pup today! 

If you think you are a perfect match for Natalie please complete an application fully: https://www.petstablished.com/organization/243592 

Natalie has been fully vetted, is up to date on all vaccinations and on preventatives for heartworm, flea, and tick. We cannot guarantee breed information. You will find price guidelines for adoption at matchdogrescue.org and you can read about the whole adoption process and what MatchDog Rescue provides with each dog. 

This gorgeous MatchDog is currently being fostered and cared for at our own facility so as to look and feel her best when she meets you on Saturday, February 13th, 2021. For the very best chance of securing a meet with this dog, you must be available all day on this date. 

If you see a pending notification on this dog, it means we have informed the lucky family selected as the best match for this particular dog and they have agreed to come to the transport/event with the goal of taking the dog to their forever home. If for any reason this plan falls through, we will change the picture back to its original format and revisit other applications.

animal.description:
Solo T. is an extremely calm, sweet 11-year-old male German Shepherd Dog who was surrendered by his owner to a shelter in Southern California. He is an easy going boy who takes a general interest in other dogs but really loves to be with his people. Solo was placed with a foster family who was amazed at how well he adjusted to a new environment. Unfortunately, Solo developed a skin condition that resulted in his return to the shelter for treatment. His itchy skin is now under treatment, making him more comfortable but still very interested in back rubs! Like most senior dogs, Solo has some arthritis but he loves to go out on short walks and walks well on leash. Solo is house trained, loves to be petted and rides well in the car. He shows no food aggression or other difficult behaviors. Solo is a very polite, quiet dog. He never nuisance-barks even when dogs around him are all barking! He is house trained, crate trained and loves treats. TSGSR volunteers love his kind, sweet disposition. Solo will make a loving, calm addition to a new family!

Solo T. Summary:
- Solo is a male, 11 yrs old, weighs 62 lbs, current on shots
- Good with Adults, middle school aged children, dogs, and travel in the car
- Cats TBD

Solo passed a set of evaluation tests before being accepted into the TSGSR. The tests are not intended to assess how smart the dog is but are important for TSGSR to determine if the dog is expected to be safe in a family home. The tested behaviors check to see if the dog will guard or protect food or toys from people, will tolerate handling all over its body (including ears, nose, lips to check teeth, lifting paws, belly, back, and gently pulling the tail) and the ability to get along with other well behaved dogs. He remained calm during all of these tests and showed no aggressive tendencies. 

Please join us in welcoming Solo to TSGSR! Check back often. We will be updating his bio as we learn more about him!

What's Next for Solo T:
Thulani Senior German Shepherd Rescue (TSGSR) will continue to see that Solo is well cared for and receives all medical care needed for his well being while in our care. In addition, TSGSR is beginning a search for an adoptive home that will care for him for the rest of his life. He will come to his new home with a supply of food, a cushy pad if wanted, and other goodies such as toys. 

Solos medical expenses will be covered for the rest of his life by Thulani Senior German Shepherd Rescue (TSGSR)!

If you want to learn more about Solo, or are interested in possibly providing an adoptive or foster home, please send us a message by clicking on the "Ask About Me" button. We will often get feedback or "updates" from a dog's foster home and as any updates become available they will be included here.

If you are reading about him on Petfinder.com sometimes an available YouTube video is not listed. If this occurs you can still view the video by pasting its URL into a new browser window or tab.

Available Video URL(s): https://youtu.be/RE1T97VRg9U

Saving one dog wont change the world. It will change the world for that one dog.

Buddy Westin is back with us and looking to find a really special home. Buddy is a very intelligent dog who has great house manners, does not need crated wile alone, will happily play with his toys, and sleep on his bed at night. 

Buddy will need an owner who can follow through with what he is learning with our trainer regarding leash walking, greeting strangers, and can help him feel safe in his surroundings. Buddy attends daycare with other big dogs but may prefer living in a home as the only pet. Buddy is not cat friendly and would do best in an adult only home. He would not do well in a busy or active home, as he would rather keep his social circle small. 

Buddy is a big boy, nearly 75 lbs and is between 3-4 years old. Our vision for the perfect home for Bud is a single person who wants a companion, is interested in dog training and can appreciate an intelligent dog, can send him to day care on occasion, likes to walk or hike, and has a fence. Adopters will have to commit to working with our tainer for a few weeks to make sure they understand how to help Buddy continue with his new skills.

animal.description:
Bonnie is a stunning Spaniel/Lab Mix. She is very sweet and active. She is fearless lol…..she is bossy and sassy and loads of fun. She is definitely a bit stronger willed than her brother Billy Ray. Her beauty and personality automatically make you smile!  She holds her own with other dogs and refuses to be intimidated!  She would make a wonderful family dog but would definitely need some patience and firm hand at first.  However, anything that cute is worth it.  She is approximately 8-9 months old and weighs around 30 lbs. She will require basic obedience, leash, crate and house training. 

Adoption fees details: 
Puppies - Adults $ 550, Seniors $375. These adoption rates include transport from Alexandria, Louisiana to designated New England adopter pick up locations and NE foster homes using either Rescue Road Trips, Pets LLC or CAFA Transport. If you do a search you will see that this is a very reasonable adoption fee and comparable to other rescues. Adoption fee breakdown:Adoption Fee:   $  365.00Transportation Fee:  $ 185.00MA and NH only--Quarantine fee if applicable:  $125.00

Medical details:
All our dogs are altered (spayed or neutered), DHLPP, rabies, Bordetella, Heartworm tested with negative test results, microchipped, treated for parasites and on monthly heartworm and flea and tick prevention. A health certificate is issued by a licensed Louisiana veterinarian.

Adoption details:  
In some instances, a meet and greet is not possible before adoption unless we have a foster home in New England available. Available for a Meeting confirms the dog is in a NE Foster home and available for a meeting in the city state provided.  Most times our dogs get adopted before a foster home becomes available - and if so, they go straight to adopters home. Foster parents talk to adopters and feel confident that this will be a match before our dogs are transported up. Also if by some chance it is not a match we have a safety net in place as we ask that adopters to let us know that it is not a match and we direct you to take the dog to a foster home or boarding kennel once that is arranged. If necessary, we will ask you to foster the dog until a foster home can be arranged. 
Transport details:Rescue Road Trips (rescueroadtrips.com), Pets LLC (petsllc.net) or CAFA Transport will deliver our precious pups on commercial rescue animal transport to designated locations.  The fee is 185.00 which IS INCLUDED in your adoption fee already.**Rescue Road Trips, was featured on The Today Show - view it at http://www.today.com/video/today/55034556#55034556

MA and NH RESIDENTS:
If you are a Massachusetts or New Hampshire residence, an additional fee of $125.00 will apply due to State quarantine fee requirements. If the dog is in a foster home in MA or NH, this fee will be added in the adoption fee regardless of where the adopters home is located making the total adoption fee $675.00 for puppies and adults $500.00 for Seniors, otherwise the full adoption fee for all other states is $550.00 for puppies and adults and $375.00 for seniors. This includes a 48 quarantine, recheck by a MA licensed veterinarian, and issued a MA health certificate.

Visit all our available dogs at www.cenlaallianceforanimals.comWe update and add dogs frequently.

We hope to help make a difference in a rescue dogs life into loving responsible homes.

**Please note Dong Dong is currently with a foster in Vancouver, BC and will only be available for adoption to residents of Vancouver and surrounding areas**

Dong Dong was rescued in 2019 from a man who was raising dogs to sell to the meat market. He then moved to our partner boarding house in early 2020 and is now with a foster family in Vancouver, BC.

He is a jindo/corgi mix with a very sweet and calm temperament with a quiet personality. Although he can be shy with humans, he enjoys being in their company, is always gentle and accepts pets and belly rubs. He enjoys stuffy toys and well as chewing on his dental sticks. Currently, he lives with 2 other small dogs who he gets along with well. He is potty trained (his foster says he’s never had an accident!) and has never shown any destructive behaviors in the home.

It is important to note Dong Dong is still getting used to being outdoors, especially if triggered by something that might scare him like a loud truck. It will be important for his adopter to be diligent with his safety. Overall, he walks well on leash and likes to greet every dog he sees on the street.

This handsome boy's ideal home is:

- A calm and low activity home with adults only, or older teenagers
- Active humans who enjoy walks, runs, hikes, etc.
- A quiet neighborhood (as the sounds of trucks and traffic still scare him)
- A home with a secure yard to run around
- A home with another friendly dog is highly preferred (another confident dog he could mirror would also help him overcome his fears)

Vaccination Details>>
DHPPL, Canine Influenza, Kennel Cough, Rabies, Corona, Heartworm test, Giardia test, Flea & tick & heartworm prevention are all done.

To learn more about the dog, or to submit your application, please follow the link.
https://www.freekoreandogs.org/adopt/dong-dong/

animal.description:
Everyone meet Junie B! Junie B is a female treeing walker coonhound around 3 years old. Like a dog who wants to go for rides? Junie is the girl for you! When she sees the car, she wants to go on an adventure! Do you have kids? Well, Junie doesn't live with any but we think she would do well with school aged kids. She may be too bouncy for little ones. Junie cannot live with cat or other small critters because she does have a high prey-drive. Junie does well with other dogs and loves to play with the active 1 year old mix breed dog in her foster home. They can play chase in the yard for hours! Junie is an active girl and needs to be stimulated. A worn out hound is a well-behaved hound! This is really important for Junie in particular. If she gets bored, she will dig holes in the yard and chew things you really don't want her to chew. 

So what would be Junie's ideal home?
-Fenced in yard to romp and play
-An active dog companion or an active family or even better....BOTH!
-A cat free home
-A family who wants to train and do obedience. Junie is smart and would love and benefit from this! 

Want to know more? Contact the good folks at HoundSong to learn more about sweet Junie B! 

HoundSong Rescue dogs are vaccinated, spayed/neutered, and microchipped. If you have questions about this dog, the adoption process, or are interested in meeting a dog, please visit www.houndsong.com and complete the adoption application. No meet and greets will be scheduled without the completion and approval of an adoption application.

animal.description:
Neptune is a medium energy dog who enjoys getting outside for a couple of walks each day. He loves a brisk walking pace! We go outside around 7 or 7:30 am and then again after breakfast around 8:30 or 9 am with a longer walk at that time. We have been going outside every couple of hours with two of those times being for longer walks. He typically eats dinner around 6 or 6:30 pm - we will go outside after dinner and again before bed around 9:30 pm.  He sleeps in his crate at night but would be fine sleeping on his pillow as well.  He is perfectly happy to spend time during the day lounging on his pillow and chewing on either his favorite stuffed rabbit or other chew toy.  He would love a home with plenty of space to run around outside to learn how to play fetch.  He gets anxious about strange noises and other dogs barking which is why it would be best for him to be in a house rather than an apartment building. 

Guests in your home will need a slow introduction to Neptune. Outside of the home / on walks he does not bark at other people. He will likely react if they have a dog with them.  Neptune would do best in a home without children, so movements are more predictable. 

Neptune enjoys walks and in addition to his bathroom trips outside typically does 2 or 3 ten-minute walks each day. His natural pace is brisk which makes it seem like he is pulling, but he will walk well and slow down a bit once he feels comfortable with his surroundings. He is good at entertaining himself indoors with toys (particularly non-rawhide type chews or stuffed toys) or naps on his pillow.

Outside of the home Neptune does react to other dogs while taking walks including barking at them but will respond to a firm sit command which reminds him that you are in control of the situation. As long as we keep walking, he will forget about the other dog. We are working on this anxiety about other dogs, but this is something that will take more practice.  He currently uses a prong collar on walks. Neptune would do best without any cats in his forever home.

Neptune attended a two week board and train program with Enlightened K9 Training in New Berlin, WI.  The trainer helped Neptune to build a solid foundation of obedience.  

Neptune tends to get anxious about being left alone, but we are working on this by practicing him being alone for short amounts of time. He is in his crate when I am out of my apartment, but he would likely be fine to be outside of the crate once he is comfortable in his new home. He does not chew on non-toys or jump on furniture. I currently work from home so he is not often left alone for very long- this is something he would need to practice. 

The vet noted some tartar accumulation so an adopter should expect a dental in the next 1-2 years.  

Neptune is a curious and sweet dog who would do best in a house environment with space to run around outside. An owner with previous dog experience would be a good fit and it should be expected that the owner will need to help Neptune when he is anxious and provide a sense of security and structure. Neptune is a happy dog, a quick learner, and eager to find his future home!

animal.description:
Izzy (female chihuahua) and Tee (male pug) are a senior bonded pair looking for their forever home.  These sweet pups ended up in foster care when their owner had to surrender them.  They have a been a joy to foster! 

Tee (who we call T-Bone) is an attention hog and is very vocal about getting his pets, often whining when he wants attention (which the pug breed is known for).  He’s also skilled at using his rear end to push Izzy and other dogs out of the way so he can get all the attention from the humans!  Meanwhile, Izzy is more laid back and can usually be found snoozing in a dog bed or on a blanket (though she also loves to get pets too).    Both of these pups can’t get enough snuggles and would prefer to be around their human as much as possible.  During the day, they are content to sleep behind me in their dog beds as I work from home, taking occasional potty breaks outside.  In the evenings, they love to be on my lap or right next to me on the couch.  They are expert cuddlers and love to give kisses! 

Despite being a little older, these pups still have some spunk! They both like to play with stuffies and Tee likes to play tug, both with humans and other dogs.  While they’ve been in our home, they’ve been exposed to lots of other dogs, most of them larger and younger than these two, since we do in-home doggy daycare.  They do well with other pups, but will sometimes bark to put other dogs in their places if they are being too hyper (but Izzy and Tee are all bark, no bite).  Izzy and Tee would do fine living with other dogs, but they would probably prefer calmer dogs or to be the only dogs in the house.

Health-wise, Tee doesn’t have any known health issues and has enjoyed taking a few longer walks (~2 miles) with other dogs in the house.  Izzy has floating patellas (kneecaps), a very common issue for her breed and small breeds generally.  This just means she walks a little more slowly and she looks a bit stiff when she walks.  However, she does well getting around, enjoys wandering around our fenced in yard (or did, before it snowed) and can get up and down our flight of stairs several times a day without issue.  That being said, she’s probably not up for very long walks.  Izzy is also totally deaf, not even vacuuming right near her wakes her up from a nap, but she says her hearing loss is a blessing because Tee snores quite loudly when he’s sleeping! Despite being deaf, Izzy manages just fine and often takes cues from Tee.  Both Izzy and Tee are pretty low energy and have minimal exercise requirements, preferring to spend most of the day snoozing, but both enjoy taking short walks outside (Tee is doing better adjusting to the cold weather; Izzy is a typical heat-loving chihuahua and prefers the hot summer sun). 

We crate Izzy and Tee at night (with both sleeping in the same crate) and occasionally during the day.  At night, they settle in and sleep through the night.  During the day, they will bark or whine if we are active in the house and they are crated (but this is true of most dogs).  They have never shown any destructive tendencies, so they likely wouldn’t need to be crated if that is what their adopter preferred.  Both are potty trained, but need to be let out every few hours to avoid accidents.  Izzy has had a few tiny “piddles” in the house while in our care, but this may be due to being spayed at an older age.  

Izzy and Tee live with their foster parents and our toddler. While they tolerate the toddler very well (she loves giving them hugs and she’s fascinated by Tee’s curly tail), given their age and size, they would probably do best in a home with older kids or no kids.  They have both been friendly to the few strangers they have met while in our care.  

Senior dogs have so much love to give, and these two are guaranteed to bring you a smile and make you laugh every day!  Their adoption fee is $300 for the pair.

Meet Holden, this handsome Doberman Pinscher is about 3 years old, and around 91 pounds. He is neutered, microchipped and up to date on vaccinations. Holden is well trained and knows come, sit, platz (down), and Fuß (heel). He walks nicely on a harness like a Wonder Walker. Although he is young Holden has been calm and obedient while in foster care. Holden is not crate trained and likes to spend the night with his person. He has not displayed signs of separation anxiety while in foster care. He rides nicely in the car and when left alone, he tends to lay down and sleep.
 
Holden has been an only dog while in foster care, so we do not have info on him living with another dog. When walking he will want to meet the other dogs, but it’s easy to just get him to keep walking. When meeting people, he’s happy to meet them. In foster care he has had no issues with adults, but has not been exposed to children. Like any large breed, he could accidently knock down a child. Holden has not lived with cats, but does bark at the feral cats when walk by outside. Holden requires an adult only home with power breed or Doberman experience. Since Holden has been fostered as an only pet with no children in the home we do not have info on him living with other dogs, cats, or children. Due to this we are looking for a home where he can be a best friend only dog, however a home with another dog may be considered if the dogs are a match and applicants are very experienced owners. RED will be requesting and following up with vet and/or trainer references and applicant will need to show they can use the dogs action cues (commands). Holden requires a fully fenced yard with a visible fence. 

If you are interested in meeting Holden please fill out an application here: http://www.rescueeverydog.org/Adoption.php
Answers to the application must sent via message on Facebook, emailed applications will not be received. 

REQUIREMENTS FOR ADOPTION:

- Adult only home
-Experienced, confident dog owner with power breed and/or Doberman experience 
- No other pets preferred, one other dog may be considered on a case by case based in a dog savvy home 
- Securely and visibly fenced yard 
- Vet/trainer references


Mandatory fenced yard. No apartments. Some Condos and homes with a private use fenced yard maybe considered. No children. Adoption donation for this companion animal is $650

ADOPTION PROCESS: 

If you are interested in adoption please fill out an application here: http://www.rescueeverydog.org/Adoption.php
Answers to the application MUST be sent via message on Facebook (we do not receive applications sent via email)

1. Once the application is received it will be reviewed by that animals caseworker. 

2. If your application is seen as a good fit to the pet you are applying for we will request photos of your fenced yard as well as your current crate or the crate you plan on purchasing. 

3. Once received we will schedule a phone interview with you to discuss the pet and the next steps, should a match be seen.  

4. Meet and greet/adoption 

PLEASE, CONSIDER SPONSORING THIS COMPANION ANIMAL IN NEED. R.E.D. RELIES ON DONATIONS TO SAVE, SUPPORT AND OFTEN REHABILITATE LIVES. WHICH BRINGS LIVES LIKE THIS TO THE FINAL GOAL OF PROVIDING A SAFE PATH TO A NEW FOREVER HOME. GO TO SPONSOR BUTTON TO HELP SAVE A LIFE! FOR MORE INFORMATION ON R.E.D. GO TO WWW.RESCUEEVERYDOG.ORG Mandatory fenced yard. No apartments. Some Condos and homes with a private use fenced yard maybe considered. No children. Adoption donation for this companion animal is $. Donations cover some of the care costs for R.E.D. animals. Like housing, supportive care, medical needs and food. All R.E.D. animals are spayed or neutered and vaccinated. Most are micro chipped with adopter registration included. R.E.D. is a 501 C3 and all donations support our life saving missions. For more information and to complete the on line adoption application on R.E.D., please, see our website at www.rescueeverydog.org. 
PLEASE READ ALL OF THE FOLLOWING TO APPLY TO ADOPT: Not all applicants will be approved for requested animals. R.E.D. reserves the right to refuse service and adoption without explanation. R.E.D. is the companion animal's advocate and will select the most suitably matched home/environment for the the companion animals emotional needs and management requirements based on each companion animal's breed(s) general needs and the unique needs of each individual animal in our care. R.E.D. requires all applicants and adopters to conduct themselves in a respectful and courteous manner. R.E.D. updates it animals adoption postings daily. If you wish to apply to adopt this companion animal go to the on line application at R.E.D.'s website www.rescueeverydog.org. and look under adoption. Before applying, please, read the following information. 
(1) Application, Phone interview, Home visit are required. Adoption Donations are generally $300 and above. Donations support R.E.D.'s life saving missions and medical and other care given.(2) R.E.D. Dogs are spayed or neutered prior to adoption, vaccinated for Parvo Distemper and generally are micro chipped. (3) You must be at least 18 years of age to complete the application or to apply to adopt a companion animal. For the safety of children and dogs and limited information on dog the dogs interaction with children- R.E.D generally prefers/requires children in adoptive home to be approximately 5 or 6 years of age and up unless otherwise noted in the dog profile. All children must be behavior appropriate with animals. (4) R.E.D. does not a ship animals to out of state adopters. Out of state adopters must come to meet the animal in person in Washington if approved for a meet and greet with a R.E.D. companion animal. Thank you.

animal.description:
PUPDATE 3

Tucker had a great Christmas! He loved curling up by the fireplace and snuggles with the whole family for movie time. Really enjoyed the treats and his gifts.

PUPDATE 2

Tucker is the kind of guy who needs frequent potty breaks and moist food. It could be a lot worse for an old guy with kidney issues. Who can’t love an old guy that hangs out with you while you work from home?! He joins you for a midnight snack in the kitchen on nights the baby refuses to sleep. He puts up with preteen shenanigans outside playing and still loves to cuddle up with her at night. He just loves everyone is and always down to hang out.

He’s a perfect starter for a family that needs someone to love. He’s super tolerant of everybody and everything. I think he’s just gotten to an acceptance age and just enjoys whatever time he can get with his peoples.

As someone with kidney issues myself—you can accomplish a lot over many years with the right diet and either none or minimal medication. It’s not an end all be all. He can still have a great life for a few more years. They say Chihuahuas can live up to 20yrs!

PUPDATE 1

Just like some old men you never know if he likes you or not. He’s not really a tail wagging playful guy. But every so often he’ll come up to you, wait for you to pet him, then lean into your head rubs. Figured this is his way of showing affection.
 
 Tucker is definitely a great guy to Netflix and chill with! Which is how he spends his days when he’s not chilling next to one of us taking a nap while we work/kids attend virtual school.

Inside the home he loves everyone that cuddles him. Outside he’s been to the groomer and interacted with several people from check-in until pick up he did well even with nail clippings. He seemed to be especially happy afterwards and spent the afternoon exploring the main rooms of the house with his tongue out.

We have 5 children ranging from just turned 1 year old to almost 14 years old. He loves anyone that will hold/cuddle him. Tucker just gets up and leaves when he’s had enough of the baby. 

Tucker is a super low energy pup. He doesn’t care if he’s on or off a leash. He just wants to do his business and go inside. He will go outside to the bathroom on and off the leash. We use an electric fence but still stay outside with him since he struggles to get up and down stairs. He does the cutest little cat like thing and covers up all his potties. He’s a little off on covering it—probably because he’s got some cataract going in both eyes???? I wonder sometimes if he was litter box trained another lifetime ago. He’s not really a go for long walks kind of guy either—but that might be weather related with the cold. He only makes it a short distance on walks with a leash before he’s tired and just stops waiting to be held. Tucker is well behaved on a leash without pulling. He just occasional side tracks to sniff.

He tends to ignore our resident dogs for the most part. Tucker just exists near them. He does understand what treats are and when they are getting some and will stand patiently near them for his turn.
 
 Tucker also prefers to take his food at his leisure all day long in the kennel. We are a multi dog family with the other dogs being much larger than him. He doesn’t bother their food—just likes his separate. Then Tucker actually eats his food. Tucker does not have cats in his foster home.

He is fine during the day—gets vocal and starts roaming the house if he’s without a bedtime cuddle buddy. Tucker likes to be near his people and might have some separation anxiety. 

He won’t sleep quietly in the kennel outside, but can make it overnight in bed with his human.
 
 That being sad—the kennel is the most comfortable way to travel by car. He gets a little anxious outside of the kennel on someone’s lap and can’t be still in a car.

Tucker has kidney disease but this doesn’t stop him from being a wonderful senior dog!  The vet recommends a prescription kidney diet food to help his condition. Tucker’s adopter will need to continue rechecks to keep an eye on it.

animal.description:
Schatzi is laid back, sweet, and very loyal to her human. If a stranger comes to the house, she will bark but is not at all aggressive. She will make a wonderful companion for someone who is home most of the time and would like an adorable sidekick to spend their days with!

She goes out and wonders around our yard in the morning and then back out after breakfast to ensure she has plenty of opportunities to relieve herself out there. She is making significant progress towards our house-training goals but will need continued work with this. Throughout the day, she wants to be near her human and will cuddle up anywhere that person is.

Schatzi has not been around children, but is easily frightened so would likely do best with older children.  She has not met a cat. 

She is a senior lady but has lots of spunk! She loves to follow her person around out in the yard when the weather is nice and uses a step to get up on to the couch. She has low exercise requirements but walks just fine on a leash and should go for a couple of short walks per day.

Schatzi currently has three foster siblings and is wonderful with all of them. She doesn't want to play but would be fine with other dogs that are respectful of her space. She does not guard her food or treats.

She has separation anxiety and will usually have an accident if left loose in the house, although she is getting better with this. She has been crated when we leave and does fine in the kennel, although is sometimes vocal. She does not chew or destroy anything when left loose and unattended.

Schatzi is a really good girl who makes us laugh every day. She is smart and learns very quickly, we are so proud of how far she has come in the short time she has been with us. She is a little love bug and will make a wonderful companion for someone who has the time to spend taking strolls and snuggling with her!

Hello world!! My name is Harry, and I am about 11 months old. I am learning everything that a puppy needs to learn. I am learning to follow commands, go potty outside, be in my crate and realize that it’s a safe place to be, and just learning how to be loved. It’s something I wasn’t shown a lot of before. One of the things that I am working on is my separation anxiety. I get scared when I can’t see my people, so I am working on understanding that it doesn’t mean that I am left alone and no one is ever coming back, it just means that I am alone for a tiny bit. I love my toys and just playing around and being a puppy. I’m still settling in, but please check back for more information or if you are sure that I am your guy for life, fill out my application and let’s be life long friends!! Your best fur friend ever, Harry (UPDATED 01/01/21)

animal.description:
AT PEPPERMINT PIG ANIMAL RESCUE, WE UPDATE ALL OF OUR PETS ON A REGULAR BASIS TO REFLECT THEIR AVAILABILITY.

IF YOU SEE ME HERE, I AM AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION. PLEASE READ MY BIO BELOW TO LEARN MORE ABOUT ME AND HOW TO APPLY TO ADOPT :)

Meet the B pups:: 3 to 5 pounds, 8 weeks old 1/2/21, Chihuahua/Pug/Terrier mixes (best guess)

Available for Adoption!

Brickle is the biggest of the girls and she is the only one with a white tail tip. She is the first to explore new things, like climbing onto the couch and attempting the stairs. Like all of her siblings, she loves to play and snuggle!

The B pups and their dad were surrendered to us on the condition that they allowed us to spay their mother. Unfortunately, we do not have a photo of their mother, but we were told she is a 10 pound Chihuahua mix. Their father, Brent (pictured) is 16 pounds and appears to be a Chihuahua/Pug mix. 

The B puppies are a playful and outgoing bunch and they are ready to find their forever homes!

$195 Adoption Fee. 

A $10.00 non-refundable application fee is required to submit your adoption application and will be deducted from your adoption fee if you adopt.

All puppies are dewormed, started on heartworm and flea prevention, and microchipped.

All puppies will be adopted with current, age appropriate vaccines, given by Peppermint Pig Animal Rescue. Peppermint Pig Animal Rescue will provide their puppy series DAPP vaccines, given at 8, 12, and 16 weeks of age.

Puppy adopters will be will be required to bring the puppy back to Peppermint Pig Animal Rescue to receive any remaining puppy vaccines after adoption. 

Puppy adopters will also be required to bring the puppy to our vet for their spay/neuter surgery after they receive their 16 week vaccination. 

The spay/neuter and puppy vaccines are included with the puppy adoption fee.

We have a strict one hour puppy adoption radius, puppy adopters must be within one hour of Peppermint Pig Animal Rescue. Please see our Adoption Radius tab on our website for more info, here:
https://peppermintpiganimalrescue.org/adoption-radius/

Along with other criteria evaluated in the adoption application, a Fenced Yard is required to adopt. 

Please see our Fenced Yard Requirements tab on our website for more information, here:
https://peppermintpiganimalrescue.org/fenced-yard-requirements/

TO CHECK AVAILABILITY of any of our adoptable animals, please go to our available pets tab, here: https://peppermintpiganimalrescue.org/available-pets-for-adoption/

All pets listed here are updated regularly to reflect their availability.

ADOPTION APPLICATION INSTRUCTIONS FOR PEPPERMINT PIG ANIMAL RESCUE:

Before completing the application, please read our ADOPTION PROCESS tab on our website, here: 
https://peppermintpiganimalrescue.org/how-our-adoptions-work/

To complete our easy online adoption application, please visit our website at PeppermintPigAnimalRescue.org.

Adoption events are held every Saturday in our thrift store from 1:00pm to 4:00pm. Please complete your adoption application in advance so our volunteers have time to screen and contact potential adopters.

IMPORTANT: All applications are reviewed in the order they are received and qualifications are based on best fit for each individual pet. A volunteer will contact you if you are selected for a meet with adoptable pet. Final approval is always made in person.

Peppermint Pig Animal Rescue is a no-kill rescue. Please consider sponsoring a pet or donating to our cause. Click the DONATE tab on our website to learn more about how you can help. THANK YOU!

For questions or inquiries on our adoptable pets, please feel free to contact our volunteer rescue team directly by submitting a Contact Form from our website, here: https://peppermintpiganimalrescue.org/contact-us/

animal.description: Hello, my name is Cyrus! I've been at the shelter for a little bit while the staff worked on my behavior. I'm ready to be adopted but I'm not a dog for a first time dog owner. I'm not very trusting of new people and I need people who understand how to manage my nervousness. When I hang out with people I tend to feed off of their energy. I need a confident and relaxed handler. I've been to playgroup with other dogs and did well. My play signals are a little mixed up and not every dog I meet may know how to interact with me. Please keep checking my profile for updates as the staff gets to know me better! If this dog has been successful in our play groups it is not a guarantee that a dog will be social with other dogs in their home or in public settings. Dogs are individuals and have personality conflicts, just like us. Play groups do not guarantee that territorial or resource guarding issues will not surface in the home. While play groups do help us get to know the dog's better, once they are adopted their new environments and new relationships will influence their behavior in ways we cannot predict. The Adoption Fee Includes: - initial canine distemper combination vaccination - first worming or stool check - rabies vaccination (for animals over 3 months of age) - AVID microchipping - flea treatment/preventative - spaying or neutering Adoption fee: $135.00 Per state law, ALL ADOPTERS must purchase a non-refundable 2021 dog license at time of adoption for any canine three months and older. The cost of the license is $7.00. (Senior Citizen or Person with Disability-$5.00) Leash and collar included

www.cockeradoptions.org

There, you will find the current status of the dog, the links to our adoption and foster applications, and detailed information about our adopting and fostering procedures.

ADOPTED! ADOPTED! ADOPTED! ADOPTED! ADOPTED! ADOPTED! ADOPTED! ALL OF MY PICTURES ARE AVAILABLE BELOW! MY ORIGINAL INTAKE INFORMATION: Hi Everyone! My name is Bella, and I just arrived at the CSAC from the kind people at Spanky's Project. I was rescued from a puppy mill. I am shy because I have not been around a lot of people or lived in a home as a pet. My perfect home will be one with dog experience that can help with my training and acclimating to the outside world. Right now, I am in the caring hands of one of the great Vets that work with the CSAC. They are checking me out and making sure I am healthy. Hopefully, I will find my new family that will help me to understand that I am a cherished family pet, not just an animal to be used to make money. For more information about this dog, email our Adoption Coordinator. Our adoption process starts with an application. If you are interested in adopting this pup, please click the Adopt menu at the top of the screen, read about our process, and click the application link. The medical and custodial care of the many Cockers in our care is tremendous. More and more dogs are abandoned with urgent and serious medical issues. We are committed to providing the best possible care for these forgotten friends. Unfortunately, the mounting high costs are beginning to limit the number of dogs we are able to take into our program. Even if you cannot adopt or foster one of our current adoptable dogs, please consider making a donation. The Cocker Spaniel Adoption Center is a 501(c)(3) non-profit charitable organization, and your donations are entirely tax deductible. Click the Donate menu at the top of the screen. For more information, visit www.cockeradoptions.org.

animal.description:
Taz
***On Medical Hold but Taking Applications***
Look at that cute tongue sticking out! This is TAZ! Taz is just 3 years old and is sweet and affectionate. He is energetic but not too hyper-he would do best in a home with a female in stead of male dog(s). We can not guarantee any of our dogs are housebroken or won’t chew things. Time and consistent training will help your new buddy adjust to their new home. This poor guy has had ulcers on his eyes-this limits his vision, but he can see. Taz has been vet checked as well and his adoption fee is $350, apply today! 

If you are interested in adopting from Boston Terrier and Short Nose Rescue of Oklahoma, please complete the Adoption Application here https://form.jotform.com/70368678829172 Please note that it can take several days to process an application as we are run entirely by volunteers, If you have completed an application, but have not heard from us within 3-5 days, please feel free to contact us. 

Please note that we are foster-based and as such, we do not have a facility to visit the dogs. 

All Boston Terrier and Short Nose Rescue of Oklahoma dogs are fully vetted at the time of adoption which includes spay/neuter, all vaccines - Rabies, Bordetella, and DHLP - along with heartworm check and the first month of preventative, and a vet check. Adoption fees vary per dog, but generally range from $150 to $450 depending on age and what vetting the dog required. The adoption fee is on a cash basis, is non-refundable, and is due at the time of the adoption. All adoption agreements state that the dog will be returned to the rescue if the adopter can no longer keep the dog for any reason. We highly recommend allowing at least a month for a dog to adjust; oftentimes settling into a new home can take time and lots and lots of patience.

While we do adopt to out-of-state adopters, we will typically not adopt outside of an approximate 1200 mile radius from Muskogee, OK with a strong preference for in state and surrounding states. We do not transport our dogs; all dogs must be picked up in Oklahoma. There are many other Boston Terrier rescues throughout the country and if we are unable to adopt to you due to your location, we will do our best to point you in the direction of the rescues nearest to you. Please contact us with any questions.

animal.description:
Needs • Canine buddy • Fenced yard (not suited for apartment living).

Sam, a stunning 1 year old, 90 pound Great Dane/Giant Schnauzer/Poodle mix, could be the sweetest dog on earth. He probably still has a bit more growing to do.  This gentle giant has no idea of his size and likes nothing more than to cuddle in the closest lap.  He loves running around with his canine foster sister and plays a mean game of fetch. His absolute favorite thing is a good belly rub, and is always ready to drop and roll over.

Sam is house trained, knows basic commands, and walks well on a leash. He is crate trained, but much prefers to stretch out on the sofa or snuggle in your bed. Highly food motivated and eager to please, Sam should have no problem learning appropriate house manners. He is friendly and playful with other dogs, and his charming goofiness makes him irresistible to everyone he meets.  Sam has established very strong bonds with his foster family and is happiest when he is with his people. He is calm and respectful in the house but needs exercise and outdoor playtime and would benefit from a home with a large fenced yard and an active canine companion. Given his size he might not be appropriate for a family with small children.  Whoever adopts this beautiful boy will reap the rewards of an amazing, loving pooch.


Thank you so much for your interest in adopting a dog from A New Chance Animal Rescue (https://anewchancear.org). We are a 501c3, tax deductible organization. ANCAR is a foster-based rescue, and we adopt within a 90 mile radius of Bedford Hills, NY.  You will find the adoption application here: (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-application/).  All fields on the application must be completed.
Please read about the adoption process (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-process/) so you'll know what to expect when you submit.   

Our dogs are in foster care and we do NOT have a shelter or boarding facility. AN APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED IN FULL AND APPROVED BEFORE A DOG CAN BE MET. This is a firm policy. Our busy volunteers are not able to respond to questions about the dog or dog meeting requests in the absence of an application.  We know these dogs very well because they are in foster care. Please read the profiles of the dog(s) you are interested in prior to submitting an application.  If there are specific requirements stated (ie: Fenced Yard or Canine Friend Required) these are included because they are vital to the happiness, health, safety and adoption success of that dog. 

We are only able to save as many dogs as we have foster homes (https://anewchancear.org/foster/faqs/) and resources for. We provide medical care including vaccinations, testing, deworming, spaying/neutering and microchipping before transporting our dogs. We provide all supplies, preventatives and any follow up vet care necessary while they are in foster care. These costs are high and the number of lives we can save is entirely dependent upon donations from people like you.  We do not receive funding from private foundations or government sources. If you can find room in your heart to help us, with any amount, we are truly grateful (https://anewchancear.org/help/donate/). We are a 501c3 organization, so all donations are tax-deductible. It is only through the kindness of supporters like you that we are 'changing lives...one tail at a time' by providing our dogs with 'A New Chance.' (https://anewchancear.org) 

Thanks so much.

animal.description:
Meet Dillon~

My name is Dillon and I am a 4 year old Shepard/Rottie mix from South Carolina.  I weigh roughly 60 lbs.

Even though I didn't have the best life so far, I am a very sweet boy. I am quiet and generally pretty calm. 

My foster family thinks I am a great dog. Unfortunately, sometimes I give a little bit of attitude to new people. Also, with a puppy I met I gave some attitude over toys and food. I have not been seen doing that with anyone else though. 
I have been through a lot in my life so these things might never develop to be an issue but my new family just needs to be sure I am trained properly!

*I am also a heartworm survivor.

 With my adorable looks, and unbridled loyalty, I will always be there for you through thick and thin. I will never judge you, or turn my back on you. Every single day, you will look at me and you will know that you are loved unconditionally. I will never betray you or hurt you, and I will grow old by your side.

******IMPORTANT - PLEASE READ ALL THE GREAT INFO BELOW******

***Please don't apply unless you are very serious about adopting, and are ready to move forward with the adoption process. We are super busy and make a great effort to respond back to EVERYONE ASAP! WHEN WE TAKE THE TIME TO PROCESS AN APPLICATION AND RESPOND BACK TO THE APPLICANT JUST TO BE EITHER IGNORED OR BE TOLD THEY CANNOT COME FOR SEVERAL DAYS, MORE TIME IS WASTED~PLEASE HAVE MORE RESPECT THAN THAT!

PLEASE read our website's ADOPTION PROCESS PAGE prior to submitting an adoption application. www.apupspizzazzrescue.com/adoption-process 
ADOPTION APPLICATION: www.apupspizzazzrescue.com/adoption-application 

ABOUT OUR RESCUE DOGS: 
 All of our dogs are located in Connecticut, are spayed or neutered, up to date on vaccines, microchipped, have been given deworming medications, and have had CT State health checks, & go home with a leash, collar, & packet of medical paperwork. 

BREED IDENTIFICATION:
Please understand that many rescue dogs are mixes of multiple breeds. Petfinder allows us to choose up to two breeds per dog. While the shelters and our rescue do our best in accurately identifying breeds, breed identification is not guaranteed. If there is a certain breed that you do not want, it is very important that you share this with our rescue when applying. When adopting a puppy, breed uncertainty plays a big part in the size/look of the dog as an adult. Please know that any puppy can be a wonderful dog, regardless of preconceived notions of certain breeds, but it is very important that the adopter has the dedication and patience to raise the puppy with boundaries, consistency, structure, & love. The more effort you give towards training & time you allow for exercise, your puppy will grow to be a HUGE source of UNCONDITIONAL LOVE, TOTAL LOYALTY, HAPPINESS, COMFORT & COMPANIONSHIP!

ABOUT OUR RESCUE:
We are a small rescue run by volunteers & focused on finding the right match for both our dogs & for you. If you are interested in adopting through our rescue, you first will need to complete an adoption application & be approved as a potential adopter before meeting any of our pups. No need to be intimidated by our application as it allows us to get to know you & your lifestyle. Of course, the more you can share the better! Please also note, while a fenced yard is fantastic, it is not required by our rescue, however, it may be required for a certain dog occasionally.  Once adoption applicants are approved to become potential adopters, we offer private appointments where you can meet one or several dogs at the discretion of the rescue. We offer a unique & pleasant experience focused on finding the perfect match. It is extremely important to us that everyone is treated with respect & that NO ONE IS LEFT HANGING. WE WILL GET BACK TO YOU WITHIN 2 TO 3 DAYS of application submission. If there is a dog you are eager to meet, please  TEXT US DIRECTLY at 203-241-2351 so that we can check the status of your application and move it forward immediately. We look forward to hearing from you and helping you find your new best friend.

*All adult dogs can be cat tested by request.

HOME/RENTER INSURANCE:
SOME PROVIDERS HAVE VERY STRICT POLICIES REGARDING WHICH TYPE OF DOG BREEDS ARE ALLOWED UNDER THEIR COVERAGE. STATE FARM WAS SUGGESTED TO US AS THEY DO NOT PUNISH, DROP, NOR REFUSE YOU DUE TO DOG BREED SHOULD YOU RUN INTO ISSUES WITH YOUR CURRENT PROVIDER.

Daisy is a Bassett Hound and Great Pyrenees mix who asks nothing more than to be with her people. She is deeply devoted and affectionate to her family. Daisy is spayed, microchipped,  heartworm negative and started on a monthly flea and heartworm preventative.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Ruckus AKA Max! If you are looking for a running partner, I am ready. I am a great family dog, fully house trained, love Netflix, not a fan of The Bachelor, and I love to share some meditation time with you on the couch. I have a bit of a green thumb as I have been known to dig a hole under the fence thinking that you may want to plant something and then I squeeze out and go for a run. I have been known to run out into traffic if not carefully watched, so please keep an eye on me! One of my very favorite places to go is the beach so that I can run around in the sand. I am a very good boy and I'd love to join you out and about as you do your daily activities, if you'll have me! I am very friendly with everyone that I meet so as far as I'm concerned, the more visitors, the merrier! I am well-trained and know my commands and I'm very good at walking on a leash. It is also smart to keep the door locked in the house and an eye on me around doors as I may take that as an opportunity to go on another run. animal.description:
Looking to add some good vibrations to your life? Look no further than Barky “Bark” Wahlberg! This 6 month old male coonhound mix is more than just devilishly handsome. He has a surprisingly deep, melodious voice that he loves using and has a very soft, plush coat. We think Bark’s going to be a big boy, as he is already 45 lbs and has some really big paws and ears to grow into. Bark is a very playful puppy, but also adores his humans above all else. He would do best as either the only dog where he can have all the attention or in a home with other playful dogs that can tire him out. He’s definitely a ladies man and can be a little shy around men. Bark is a very sensitive dog that loves to cuddle with his foster mom and will require positive reinforcement. All he wants is love.  He is crate trained and house trained. While Bark doesn’t have a third nipple (he probably has more) he does have rear dew claws unlike most dogs, making him extra special. This sweet boy is going to make a great companion and is certainly a dog for the people. Are you ready to make Bark Wahlberg a part of your funky bunch? Bark's adoption fee is $400.00.

To adopt this pet, please visit https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt

All of our dogs come spayed or neutered, fully up to date on vaccinations, including rabies (if age appropriate) and bordetella, are microchipped, heartworm negative, current on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, dewormed, and treated for any ailments found upon veterinary examination. The adoption fee covers a portion of these services, and makes it possible for us to continue rescuing animals.  

For more information on the adoption fees and the adoption process, please complete our adoption application here: https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt - an application allows us to get to know your family better so we can assess whether the animal you are interested in is a good match for your home. An application does not obligate you to adopt. Please understand that due to the volume of applications some animals receive, we are unable to contact all applicants. If your application is considered a good fit for the dog you are interested in, or even a different pet, a volunteer will give you a call as soon as possible.  

We are a foster based rescue and do not have a shelter location where dogs can be seen during the week. Please see our Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/LouiesLegacy for our weekly adoption album if you are interested in meeting a dog in person. Not all animals attend every adoption event, please check our Facebook page for animal event times and locations before you make a trip to meet a specific animal.

Thanks so much for caring about a needy animal!

Aliza is a 9-10 year old, American Eskimo female who is looking for her new forever home. Aliza is such a love and has spurts of puppy energy. Our adoption fee is $500. This includes spay/neuter, microchipping, deworming, and all age-appropriate vaccinations.

animal.description:
pet id 
46251564

Frank the Tank!  This guy is a big meatball that loves life.  He's a gentle giant and is as sweet as they come.

He's about 6 years old and was found as a stray.  He has some bald spots and pressure points but we know with some TLC he will shine.  He's absolutely beautiful despite this, and is a real head turner.  He is a beefy boy but has really good manners on leash and respects your space.  He loves to come in close for a cuddle and is a really "warm" dog.  He has shown signs of being housetrained.
 
During his assessments he showed us he really didn't want to have much to do with the other dogs, so we are betting he'd be happiest as king of the castle or with a dog that is going to match his mellow personality and a family that will make sure it is a happy match.  He also really loves food and rawhides, so a home that is going to help him adjust to the good life is his best fit.   

He is sponsored by Danahy Real Estate with a reduced adoption fee and funds towards training classes to take with his new family.



Because of the COVID19 situation, the shelter is closed to the general public. If you would like to meet any of the adoptable dogs, please fill out an application online (if you are not already pre-approved) , call the shelter, and leave a message with your name and phone number and the dog you're interested in. Have patience, and they will call you back when they can. From there, a time will be scheduled for you to come and meet the dog. Please be patient, and remember they are very short staffed at the moment.

Applications can be found at https://friendsofcbas.org/adopt

I've only been gone for maybe 15 minutes at the most so far, but every time i've come back she is usually just relaxing on or next to the couch when l come in! animal.description: Pets come to ACSKC for many reasons: they can be lost and need someone to help reunite them with their family, they can be a transfer from one of our partner shelters, or their family simply may not have the means to care for them anymore. When Cardis owner passed, she and a black cat named Jack were brought to us.Upon arrival, it was apparent that Cardi needed some TLC. She had little fur on her back due to a bad case of fleas that led to a skin infection. We found out pretty quickly that this girl does not care for baths, or any kind of experience that involves water. Cardi wasnt happy about her regular trips to the bathtub, but it had to be done in order to administer the medicated shampoo she desperately needed. Thankfully, Cardis fur has now grown in again, and she has the most beautiful brindle coat! Cardi is a very friendly 2-year-old pittie. She becomes excited whenever we walk up to her kennel, doing a whole-body wiggle when she knows its time for walks and playtime. When shes in the Big Yard, she runs around happily, and will chase anything you throwballs, sticks, frisbees, and rope toys. We think she would do best in a home that has a yard, and would get along great with older kids who she can run around and tucker herself out with. Cardi showed signs of resource guarding with other dogs, but she doesnt mind when they walk by her on the trails. We think she would be happiest if she could be a familys one-and-only pet. Come and meet Cardi by heading to kenthumane.org to submit an application! Due to COVID-19 precautions, the Animal Care Shelter for Kent County is open by appointment only. Once your application is approved, we will set up an appointment with you!Animal meetings and adoptions by appointment only. Please go to kenthumane.org/adoption-applicationOnce approved we will call you to set up an appointment!

animal.description: Its that time right after the holidays, when the festivities have come to an end, the decorations have been packed away, and everything feels a bit dimmer in the cold January light. While many of us are feeling low, here is a dog thats holding out hope for an upswing. Sherbert arrived at ACSKC after our Animal Control Officers were alerted about a case of neglect. The puppy they found was locked in a crate and barely 20lbshalf the weight he should have been at his age. Now, Sherbie is doing just fine! His weight is good and he does not show signs of any health problems or distrust in people. In fact, he becomes very excited upon meeting new friends! Just over a year old, Sherbie still has a lot of puppy energy. He loves to chase balls, run around our Big Yard, and get in some cuddles. This active pittie not only needs an outlet for all his energy, Sherbie should also work on his obedience training. While he is very food-motivated and will sit and offer his paw for treats, he could use a review of the basics. As Sherbert gets super excited when he sees someone he wants to meet, this can result in leash pulling and jumping. He will also get mouthy when playing. For this reason, we think he would do well in a home with older kids, and with another dog he can romp around with.If youve been looking for a way to get out of a slump, this lively and loving puppy is just what you need!Animal meetings and adoptions by appointment only. Please go to kenthumane.org/adoption-applicationOnce approved we will call you to set up an appointment!

animal.description:
If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interested in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

319-372-2274

All medical medical work is completed prior to adoption including spay shots worming flea treatment rabies shot micro chip heartworm test negative and vet exam. 
The adoption application is available on the website www.prairiepawsrescue.com and go to the adopt link to download the jotform application fill it out and submit. 
Prairie Paws Rescue does not adopt on a first come basis but who will provide the best home suited to the pets needs.

animal.description:
Breaking news... there's a puppy at Frosted Faces! Allow us to introduce Ysabel!

5-month-old Ysabel was found by one of our adopters when camping in Santa Ysabel. She was running down a trail with anther dog, and they were only able to catch her. We advised that they should have animal control impound her for a suitable stray hold in case anyone was looking for her, even though we suspected backyard breeding had happening, and she was likely dumped for having impairments.

Ysabel is blind and deaf, so we wanted to spring her as soon as possible from the scary shelter and also make sure she had an advocates for life - Frosted Faces and her future forever family. On December 31st, we exited Ysabel from Bonita Shelter. The other dog Ysabel was seen running with, was later caught and impounded also. When we called to check on her, staff said she had fewer impairments than Ysabel and already a scheduled adoption appointment. YAY!

Ysabel is truly a puppy and plops her big clumsy puppy paws on you, and play bows! Her adaptability is impressive, and she is very sweet and affectionate. We took Ysabel to College Animal Hospital where her bloodwork was normal except for having a UTI, so we started her on antibiotics. Ysabel has spay surgery scheduled later this month.

Ysabel is living in a foster home while she awaits a patient forever family who will give her the wonderful life she deserves. Her Foster Mom reports that Ysabel is very loving and cuddly, gets along well with the other pup in the home, and understands that the front door means potty and will hang out in that area when she needs to go. What a smart cookie!

Apply to meet sweet Ysabel: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm.

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees and we help with medical costs!

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated 1/11/21 KG

animal.description:
Meet Allen!

Allen is a paralyzed pup who isn't afraid to love fiercely after all he has been through in his short life. He is 2 years old and just 12 pounds. He was hit by a car and left dragging himself but you would never guess he was failed. He adores his humans, and craves affection. His favorite place in the world is being on a couch wrapped in the arms of the person he loves. He has overcome a lot and continues to get stronger with each week. He enjoys going on walks in his wheel chair and when he isn't in his wheelchair, he can zoom around the house and yard like its nobody's business! When he really wants to move at fast speed, he starts to hop and you'd be amazed by the skill in this! He has lived in a home with many dogs, cats, and a 4 1/2 year old gentle boy. He wants to be included in the fun and festivities, but also is good with some chill time sunbathing. Allen does require some extra steps in his daily care but it doesn't take long for this to become part of a normal routine (his current fosters have never taken care of a special needs dog before). He needs his bladder expressed a few times a day because he lost that control when he was hit. For this reason he also wears a belly band, because he does leak some, more so when his bladder is fuller. Allen had to learn for himself as well on how to embrace his new life. He benefits from basic physical therapy at home, and may even reward you with a tail wag. Allen would do best in a home with a family that is home more often than not and has a calmer small/medium size dog as a companion for him, he can also handle cats. Allen's facial expressions don't change much and we call it "resting Allen face" , but even though his facial expressions don't show it; he is a happy boy! He does get into playful moods where he will start having "zoomies" and carrying around big toys (he LOVES big stuffed toys). Allen is just looking for love (the more cuddles the better in his eyes) and someone who will accept him for who he is. Hopefully that's you! 

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

WI Dept. Of Agriculture License Number: 474085-DS

I am a mixed breed dog. This means I don't have a specific recognizable breed. The rescue uses the following guide which are guesses based on my current size and age for how big I will be when full grown: Mixed Breed (small) up to 25 pounds - Mixed Breed (medium) between 25-45 pounds - Mixed Breed (large) more than 50 pounds. Our adoptions must be done in person and we do not arrange transport to adopters. Our adoption fees vary and we are only able to accept payments by card* at this time but include spay/neuter, heartworm test (dogs), FeLV/FIV test (cats), age appropriate vaccines and deworming, flea, tick and heartworm medication and microchip.

Moka von Mosbruch is a beautiful 4-5 year old German Shepherd.  This sweet girl came to us with King from a home where she had experience being around children and enjoyed just hanging out. She is very bonded with  King. On leash, she is most comfortable with him at her side. She follows his cues but will defer to you too. Moka is a good size girl and has experience with basic commands like sit and stay. She has shown excellent house and yard manners as well. She doesn’t seem to pay much mind to other dogs, whether she’s on leash or when in playgroups. She just lets them romp and comes back to you looking for attention and encouragement. She is really looking for a home that has a little extra room for her and King. So if you are looking for a good girl like Moka with the bonus of a good boy like King, too, please fill out an application.

He is bonded with his kennel mate, Moka, and you can always sense him looking for her anytime she’s not in his line of sight.  But when reunited, he comes out of his shell and is ready to get out to explore, following your lead. A handsome boy with a medium energy level, he has a lovely dark coat and enjoys receiving affection from his people, as well as giving some back to them.  When around other dogs, he doesn’t pay them much mind - he walks past them when on leash and, when off leash, he meets dogs well and just wants to hang out.  King came to us with Moka from a home where he was good with children and showed very nice house and yard manners.  Like many Shepherds, he’s quite smart and has learned commands like stay and sit. animal.description:
Bryce von Baunatal is a beautiful, 6-7 year old German Shepherd. He has the eyes of an angel and the heart of a saint. To him, age is just a number and does not identify his energy and ability -- Bryce defies those stereotypes. He's a happy boy with bursts of enthusiasm, especially when he knows he’s about to go for a walk. This goofy boy may pull on leash but will settle in to a nice trot alongside you. He does well in playgroups; he socializes with staff and other dogs, and enjoys exploring the play yard. He is not a fan of pushy pups, so will do best with friendly canine pals. He absolutely enjoys affection from his people and, if you can imagine that release of excitement, then he will surely not disappoint, and you can’t help but laugh at his silliness. He is the perfect mixture of grace, gratitude and positivity, and he will surely make a family gush with pride. Bryce will patiently wait for you, but don’t wait too long.

animal.description:
Angelic senior lady Zara is one who we could not leave behind at Chicago Animal Care and Control this past New Year's weekend! We had seen her when she first arrived there as a stray in early December and she was completely emaciated. She still needs to put on weight and acts like she has never eaten a treat before the way she drools and devours them (but wont take your finger off, don't worry!) but she looks so much better!

Zara is much more petite in person that she looks in pictures, she is around 50lbs. She may be 9 years old but she has lots of energy and a zest for life for sure! She loves to run, play, walk, and explore. She is super loving with all people and will promptly roll over for belly rubs! She is just so cute and so deserving of a home after all she has been through.

Zara looks as though she was used to have many litters and then dumped. That may explain why she doesn't want dogs all up in her personal space, but she totally ignores them on walks and through barriers, she just does not seem to want to play very much but this may change as she gets more comfortable, especially now that she is in a foster home! But it would not surprise us if Zara's ideal happily ever after involved her as the only child and center of attention! She deserves to soak up tons of love in her golden years and she will return it in spades!

Zara's loooves her foster mama and her foster mom loves her right back. Haley thinks that Zara is the coolest and best dog!

She says that she is so friendly and loving, housebroken, she is easy to walk on a leash, was an angel for her bath, loves car rides so gets to go on lots of errands with her foster mom, and really craves being next to her person and will sleep at your feet if you are there. Zara is so good she even walks with booties to protect her little paws from the salt and she does so well on them! Most dogs would NOT tolerate that! But Zara never complains. She is an angel.

Zara does cry at first when left alone, so an apartment may not be ideal but she is currently being fostered in a town home and it is not so loud, and will stop after a bit. But she may have that separation anxiety, and in time that gets better too.

All in all, Zara is a wonderful and deserving lady! We can't wait to get her into her forever home! 

Zara's fee has been generously sponsored by a local business, Small Oven Pastries! We thank them so very much for that, and not only that, but Zara's adopter will receive a beautiful gift basket of coffees and pastries as well. Wow! Better get to that application....

animal.description:
Meet Five-year-old Falcon who is part of a bonded pair with his brother Semper. These brothers need to find a home together. They had been living with their actual mother dog and owner up until recently. (Falcon is in the blue-collar and Semper in the red collar)

Both are very sweet and loyal boys, they like to follow you around the house and be included in all your daily activities. Falcon is a bit on the shy side at first, but one he is comfortable with his family, he will open up and become a snuggle bug! They are housebroken as long as you don't leave them alone for long periods of time. They also both do well with other dogs and we cannot see them caring about cats. They are good with kids and will fit in well in a household with kids 10 and older.

This dynamic duo have already been neutered and are up to date on vaccines. They are being fostered here in New England so they are available for a Meet and Greet!! Please fill out an application to adopt these sweet brothers!

animal.description: Meet handsome King who came to us just because he was a little too active for his senior owner after the kids moved away. King's previous owners loved him a lot and said that he is affectionate and friendly and loves to play fetch. This smart boy already knows sit, down, shake and come but also looks forward to learning more! His previous home did not have any other animals, but we have introduced him to play group and he seems pretty tolerant of other dogs being around. It is very clear though that he prefers the attention of people more than anything. He is a high energy boy, so if you're looking for a couch potato, this probably isn't the dog for you. If you like being active, walking, hiking or playing ball, King might be the perfect adventure buddy! His previous owner said one of his favorite things about King was how loyal he is, and we love how eager he is to hang out with our volunteers and learn new things. If you want to bring King into your castle, schedule a virtual adoption counseling appointment today!

animal.description: Spunky Senior Alert! Spunky Kuriyana is basically the Betty White of the dog worldShe may be considered a senior, but dont tell her that! This 10 year old German Shepherd loves playing with her tennis ball, and if you dont throw it for her fast enough, she will do it herself! Kuriyana came in with another dog who has already been adopted, and in play sessions she is a bit assertive with other dogs, but could probably live with one as long as they dont mind shes a bit sassy. Kuriyana has shown us that she already knows sit, down and shake, but shes very motivated to learn even more! Kuriyana is on a couple of medications that are pretty common for older dogs, but we can go over those a bit more if youre interested in adopting her!
