animal.description:
This pretty lady is Sable, and she is a very timid but very, very sweet girl! She weighs about 25lbs, is 1-2 years old, and while we dont necessarily know her breed mix...she likes to curl up into a little ball resembling a fawn when she sleeps. Sable will do best in an all-female home. She was previously in a home with males (it doesnt matter if its adults or children), and she didnt really begin to thrive until she moved to a foster with no males in the household. In addition, a quiet home with little traffic/visitors, and minimal household members would be best. Sable gets stressed when there is a lot of commotion, so would also need a home with either no kids or older kids (15+). She does take some time to adjust, but once she settles in she really loves sitting on/next to a warm lap every chance she gets! And Sable LOVES sleeping! She can nap, nap, and nap some more! She also likes having a spot on the couch or bed where she can retreat to if she needs to feel safe/secure. Sable loves making a nest out of blankets, especially fleece ones. She loves kongs (filled with peanut butter, of course!), bully sticks, and any kind of treat! She is still learning how fun balls and toys can be, but we are confident shell learn in her own timing. She really enjoys car rides, and she doesn't mind baths! She does great on walks and walking on-leash, but if you have to miss a day of walking she really doesnt mind. She'll just nap a little extra that day! Sable will need another doggie friend in her forever home to help her confidence + show her the ropes, but she really prefers other mellow dogs. Hyper dogs can freak her out/confuse her, and she tends to bark at them. She also alerts her foster family when there are any visitors, as they do make her nervous (when the mail comes, someone gets close to the fence, walks by, etc.). Sable can jump very high, so a 6ft(+) fence will be required in her forever home. When it comes to potty-training, Sable won't ask to go outside so potty breaks do need to be offered to her. She does great with a good, consistent routine established by her people. We know that Sable needs a very special home, but if you give her just a few weeks of bonding time she will definitely open up and begin to show her sweet, cuddly side more and more. She just needs a patient mama/BFF/sidekick and a low-key home. She is SO incredibly sweet and has so much love to offer. Lets find Sable the forever she deserves! 

If you are interested in adopting Sable, please submit a general adoption application at https://newleashdogrescue.com (or private message us if you are already preapproved!). 

**Sables $200 adoption fee includes her spay, vaccinations, heartworm test, and microchip.

animal.description: Pepper Anne is such an enthusiastic tail wagger! If the Olympic Games included a tail wagging game, she for sure would win it. It's her way of greeting every time she hears or sees her human friends, and if she's near a wall, you'll hear thump, thump, thump. This loving, gentle girl has been getting along well with her Great Dane dog buddy in her foster home. She also loves playing with her toys, both soft or hard ones. She has a neurological issue in her hind end that interferes with her ability to walk well, so she can walk nicely on her leash, but only slowly. As a house-trained girl, she can free roam in the house, and has done well when home alone. And she answers to 'uh uh if asked to back off from any activity. Pepper Anne just hopes for lots of love in a very low-energy home. Come meet her and she'll wag and wag to greet you. Follow her on Instagram: celenas_fosters.

animal.description: Good luck saying no to these adorable puppy dog eyes! Chewy is a happy, content boy, though you'd never know it from the constant concerned look on his face! He loves to be petted, and if you stop petting him, he'll gently remind you with a paw on your hand. He also loves to nap at your feet or in his bed - his favorite place in the whole world. Chewy loves a nice walk and he's very eager to meet every dog he sees, happy to calmly sniff them. At home, he is mostly content hanging out on the couch watching Netflix with you, although he's been a big help with the yard work (sleeping on all the tools)! He would love a doggie housemate, and should be great with kids. But he is a bit too eager to meet and chase a cat, so should do best in a cat-free home. His incredibly gentle demeanor and kind, calm disposition will win you right over. He is a breeze to have in the house. He rarely ever barks, is great on walks, and is a perfect angel sleeping on the couch and free roaming at night and while his fosters are away. It would take a lot to bother this easy going guy! If you're looking for a shorty to snuggle with or an empath and a confidante to share your worries with, give Chewy a visit - he may be your perfect match!

Emmitt was in foster care for 4 months in Tulsa after getting hit by a car and having his leg amputated. He arrived in Minnesota on January 2nd. He hasn't had any accidents in the house, enjoys car rides, likes to go for walks and is doing great on a leash now that we have a harness that fits him. Emmitt loves cheese, belly rubs and chasing a ball in the snow.

I am ready to find my new forever home.

Adoption Fee $500 +taxes/fees

If you would like to meet me please fill out a pre-adoption application at www.tailsrescue.org

Happy Tails Adoption Center is open on Sundays from 12-5pm. We are located at 7940 University Ave NE, Fridley. Dogs are at events based on the availability of their foster family. Please fill out a pre-adoption application so we know you are interested in meeting/adopting one of our animals. The breeds of our dogs and cats are a 'best guess.' We often do not know what mix they are and have to base it on what we think they look like, and base it on breeds often found in the area they came from. Most of our dogs who have gotten DNA tests done are 4-10 breeds mixed together. Because their breed mix is a guess we cannot guarantee a 'full grown size' of many of our younger animals.Interested in adopting me? Click here to fill out an application!Happy Tails Rescue Minnesota is located at 7940 University Ave NE, Fridley MN 55432. We are open for adoption events from 12-5 every Sunday. If there is a certain animal you want to meet at one the events please fill out a preadoption application to directly contact their foster family or check our Facebook page to see if they will be there! Their event attendance is based on the availability of their foster family.
Home visits (video tours or in person) are required for all dog adoptions. All of our cats and dogs are INDOOR pets and are NOT to be left outside unattended (even in a fenced yard), or running loose!

animal.description:
Hi everybody! I am Ginger and I am glad you came to meet me. I am a female short hair collie mix that is about 3 years old and I weigh about 60 pounds. You might have seen my story of how I was listed to be euthanized at a shelter until Purple Power Animal Welfare Society (Purple PAWS) stepped in and rescued me. I am the famous momma that delivered 11 puppies in the car while I was traveling from Oklahoma to Kansas.
I am very friendly and the thing I want the most is to be with my people. I absolutely love being by your side and getting pet, and belly rubs. I am house trained and do not have accidents as long as you take me outside every few hours. I will come and ask to go out when I need to go. I have had the run of the house since I came to live with my foster family and I have never been destructive while at my foster home.
I have never met a person that I do not like. I get along well with other dogs if they do not growl at me and I like to play tug-o-war with them (and you). I might need a slow introduction to become friends with another dog. I am living with cats now and we get along well (I mostly just ignore them). I do NOT get along with the chickens. I am learning to walk on a leash and am getting good at not pulling (unless I find a smell that needs investigated). I know “sit”, “go potty”, “go to the house”, “come”, and “stay”. I will bark when someone comes to our house but once I meet them, they are my good friends.
I am an active girl and need lots of exercise. I really need a farm or large fenced yard where I can run and play. I would not do well in an apartment or home without a fenced yard. I like to play with a dog friend but I would also do well as an only dog. I would be a great jogging partner.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

I'm Miguel. More information on me coming soon!

Animal Rescue of the Rockies believes that every pet should find a wonderful, caring home. To ensure each pet finds the best possible home, we ask that you fill out our Adoption Application so we can learn more about you and your household. We review each application we receive and will contact you within 48 hours. If your home sounds like a good match for you and the pet, the next step is to set up a "meet and greet." After meeting the pet, if you would like to proceed with adopting, we'll ask that you read and sign our Adoption Agreement and pay the adoption fee. Our adoption fees help cover the costs of saving more lives! A home visit will be scheduled within one week of your new pet going home with you.

The adoption fee for this pet is $300. Our adoption fee covers the following:

- Spay/Neuter, Microchip

- DAPP vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for all DAPP boosters after adoption.

- Rabies vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for any rabies vaccinations after adoption.

If you are interested in adopting, please fill out an adoption application by clicking here . We want our pets to go to a lifelong new home, so thank you for your patience during the adoption process!

Please email ARRColorado@gmail.com for more information, as we can not accept calls at this time. Our adoption process is:

1. Fill out our Adoption Application online. We'll contact you within 48 hours to answer any questions you may have about the pet.

2. If the pet looks like a great match, we'll schedule a meet and greet and ask you to fill out our online Adoption Agreement if you'd like to proceed with adopting. Once you've completed the Adoption Agreement and pay the pet's Adoption Fee, you can arrange to pick up your new furry family member!

animal.description:
Pete is a playful, intelligent Pittie mix who is 2 years old and weighs 70 lbs.  He is a happy, friendly, obedient boy with medium energy and good leash manners (he walks nicely on the leash and likes to stay next to his person). He was the longest resident at a rural GA shelter when a BarkVille volunteer saw him and offered to foster him so BarkVille could save him.  When Pete first left the shelter he was frightened of everybody & everything, would not walk on a leash, and had to be picked up to go outside.  He has come a LONG WAY since then, but is still scared of brooms, mops, rakes and will cower if you raise your hand.  He has been working daily with his foster family to overcome his fears and although he is still a little timid and shy with new people, he loves to give hugs, go for car rides, run around outside, and play with all the other dogs in his foster home. He is looking for a home with a fenced yard where he can play outside with his people and his dog friends.  He is housebroken, crate trained, neutered, fully vaccinated & microchipped.  He was HW+ when he came to BarkVille and is currently available for a foster to adopt situation until his HW treatment is complete and he is medically cleared for adoption. If you are not familiar with Heartworm disease, dogs get it from mosquitos and it is not contagious. It is easily prevented & highly treatable, but requires extended rest during treatment.  

For more information about Pete, please email us at info@barkvilledogrescue.org. If you would like to adopt this sweet boy, please submit an application for him at https://www.barkvilledogrescue.org/applications

animal.description:
We all need a little HOPE for 2021, how about a lot of HOPE??!!!

My name is HOPE and found myself abandoned at an empty field house at a local school that is no longer in service. A kind lady saw me and started feeding me for a few days.  I quickly bonded and wanted to follow her car home each day and this was a concern of hers, as I was probably safer there at the field house. 

On News Years Day 2021 while feeding me, a neighbor happened to see her doing this and stopped to ask a few questions. As luck would have it this neighbor just happened to have the number to a volunteer with BFF Pet Adoptions. One phone call and my 2021 is off to pretty darn good start!!

I was taken into rescue and give the spa treatment, a much needed bath, flea prevention, my ears were cleaned and I now have a warm safe place to sleep and a full tummy in the care of BFF. 

I am up to date on my vaccines, have been spay, microchipped and am heartworm negative and on monthly preventative. My adoption fee is $175.00.

I am a large girl, born round April 2020, so most likely will have some more growing to do. I weigh about 66 lbs, so just saying if size is an issue, WE ARE NOT A MATCH!!

I am very sweet and very smart, I do pretty good with the "sit" command, I know down(as in laying flat on floor), leash walking is a work in progress, but I do fairly well at that if guided and know what is expected of me. I like to jump up on people, but when told "no", I usually retreat. I am strong willed and I need and desire training. I need a family that will give me regular exercise and be patient and committed to me for the rest of my life. This training is how I will bond with my people. 

I am am a leaner, typical of the hound, meaning I want to be close and will lean up against you when possible. I want to be close to you. Coonhounds are happy to lay around and chill, but also can be rambunctious without regular exercise. Heelers are, as a rule, HIGH ENERGY, they are a working breed and need a job and form strong bonds and can become possessive.

My ideal home would be one with a committed family, older children, a large fenced area and some activity to help work off energy. I do love the water, so a pool would be a plus. 

PLEASE DO YOUR HOMEWORK ABOUT THE BREED OR BREEDS BEFORE YOU ADOPT A PET. The fewer surprises the better FOR ALL!!

If you think we may be a match, there is an application process that doesn't lock you in to adopt, it just gets the process started. There is also a home visit required and that can be done, location is not an issue.

PLEASE REMEMBER WHEN ADOPTING A PET, IT CAN BE A 15++ YEAR COMMITMENT. ADOPT RESPONSIBLY!!!!

Breed: Aussie mix

Andy is a good looking teenager who has had a few homes already. He will need an experienced owner willing to work him so that he can learn good doggie manners and become a balanced boy. Andy can be reactive to new people and some dogs. He loves to train, play with his toys, go for walks/car rides, and chew on his treats. He is still a teenager who needs lots of exercise and training. Andy has displayed separation anxiety so he will need an understanding owner who can help him him cope and won’t leave him all alone until he can handle it. Based on Andy’s history and current needs, he is not suitable for condo or apartment living and should not be expected to visit dog parks. He is also not recommended for homes with children, cats or other dogs. While he has been great with some dogs, he really needs to build his confidence and get settled before another dog shares his living space.

If you want to adopt Andy and you can meet his needs, please fill out an adoption application http://aussierescuesandiego.org/foster-and-volunteer/adoptionapplication/. Please answer every required question, otherwise your app will not submit. You will receive an immediate confirmation once it has been submitted. animal.description:
Emmeline was a transfer from Spokane Humane Society because she needed diagnostics they couldn't do at their clinic. She is 3 years old, and was an owner release to SHS with a history of "over 2 years chronic vomiting". Never been to a veterinarian as far as we can tell (ie, not vaccinated, not spayed, and at no point  did they go get this dog's life-long GI issue even looked at, let alone treated.

Humans are the best.

She was 37# at presentation and should be 50-60. SHS did blood work, which showed normal liver and kidney function. When we got her up to Chewelah Veterinary Clinic, we did radiographs of basically the whole dog, which showed a severely distended esophagus and basically empty intestines. This is a condition called megaesophagus in which her esophageal muscles stop working and don't move food down to the stomach. It just sits in the esophagus, and falls back out through the mouth with gravity if the head is lowered. Given Emmeline's age and the duration of issues reported, this is most likely a congenital issue which has been worsening over time with lack of treatment.

We started on feeding in an elevated position and remaining upright after feeding - so far so good, and no regurgitation since starting upright feeding the end of November. Unfortunately, there's not really a way to reverse the changes in her poor, stretched-out esophagus, so she'll be a bit of a dietary management challenge for life.

The area outlined in green on the radiograph here is her esophagus, which SHOULD be a direct tube about 3/4" diameter from mouth to stomach. Not, you know, half the diameter of her thorax.

Emmeline has bulked up to a much healthier 50 pounds, and has now been spayed and vaccinated. She's recovered well from surgery and is ready to find her permanent home. She gets along well with other dogs and with cats, no problems with horses and is scared of turkeys, but she will chase chickens. She loves car rides, and thinks the entire couch belongs to her.

If you're interested in finding out more about Emmeline, adopting her, or donating toward the cost of her care, please contact Jes at docjesadams@gmail.com, or 509-690-7343.

animal.description:
RANDOLPH DUKE ~11 months old. Good with dogs. Kids TBD. Not good with cats.

GSRA adopts to residents of VA, NC, and SC

Randolph is a dog who loves life and won't let his rough past keep him down! Though we don't know much of his history, we do know he did not have much consistency in his former homes and was treated more as property than a member of the family.
Things have changed for this pup and he has had a chance to show his goofy personality and good natured soul. Randolph is a happy go lucky dog who is truly a family dog and just wants to be with his people - wherever you are, he will be! He his perfectly content sitting in your office while you do work, laying in the kitchen while you cook, or snuggling with you on the couch while you catch up on trash tv.

Randolph is still puppy age and therefore very playful - thankfully, he has a dog companion here in my home and they keep each other occupied much of the day! Randolph is very courteous of other dogs is quick to be submissive to gain a playmate. He shares toys and treats with no issues and shows no signs of resource guarding.
Randolph is house trained, is not a chewer and is very respectful of your home and belongings - he does know what his toys are though and will DESTROY a dog toy with a squeaker - you have been warned! He is the best sleeping buddy and and snuggler.

Randolph LOVES to go outside - he does good in car rides - especially if he can stick his head out the window! He still pulls a little but nothing severe - he has a harness that works pretty well. I have not run with him but have a feeling he would be a great running buddy. He also loves water.

Randolph is crate trained and can be left up to 6 hours. When I first started fostering him, he would cry for 30 minutes or so, but within two weeks, he has improved nearly 100% and goes in with no problem with no whining. Due to his past, he has separation anxiety and this was not unexpected behavior.

Randolphs weird fact: he has a licking fascination...I've seen him lick table legs, aluminum posts, blankets, the weirdest things... he's unique!

PLEASE NOTE: It is GSRA policy that we do not adopt dogs under the age of 1 year old to families with children under the age of 8 years old.

For more information on our adoptable pet list please visit: Adoptable Pet List

Please join us at our next Event(s):

Current Scheduled Events:

animal.description: Layla is a sweet, cuddly, playful and smart 6-8 month old baby. She is a typical puppy- loves making friends at daycare, running zoomies, playing with toys, chilling by you on the couch and generally curious. She is also pretty attentive and listens to her person (for the most part- she is still figuring out her new name and what some of the words mean). She knows how to sit, and immediately learned wait when mommy was putting food in her bowl. She should be easy to train. She is still a tiny bit mouthy when she gets excited (as most puppies are), but immediately understands when told to stop. She LOVES her crate and will go there herself when she tires out. She loves exploring the backyard and watching the birds and chasing bunnies. And let's not forget running zoomies. She would do best in a home where she has a place to run, or will be exercised well. She would make a great running buddy. We are still working on her house-training. But a good schedule (probably 3-4 times a day) and the fact that she is crate trained means she will get there soon. She sleeps through the night without needing to go out. She is a fantastic family pet, and ideally would love a family with a play buddy. She lives with 5 other dogs in her foster home and does great with them (even with a few grumpy housemates).

animal.description:
Meet Murphy!

This handsome Red Heeler mix pup is about  2 1/2 years old and finds himself in need of a new home through no fault of his own.  A change in living circumstances made his family (who adopted him from JoJo's as a young puppy) unable to keep him.  

Murphy is getting along great with dogs of all sizes in his foster home.  He likes children, but we think toddlers would be too small to be happy with this active boy.  Heelers like to heel, including toddlers, so older children or an adult household would probably be best for Murphy.  Another dog or two to play with or an active person who enjoys playing with and training their pups would be great for Murphy.

He loves car rides, we do not know if he likes cats or not, he is housebroken but may need watching when he first changes homes, and crate trained.

Although Murphy is a good boy, smart and willing to please, he does need work on manners.  If you have a heart for heeling breeds and know how to work with them, we'd love for you to meet Murphy.  He's going to make a wonderful addition to the right home.

If you are interested in meeting Murphy, please email us at jojosdogrescue @gmail.com and we will send you an application, or download one from our website www.jojosdoghouse.com.  Adoption fee is $175 and includes neuter, up-to-date vaccinations, microchip, and parasite treatment and prevention.  Thanks for choosing adoption!

Please visit our Facebook page JoJo's DogHouse (non-profit) to learn more about us and see many of the dogs we have rescued.  We hope you'll join JoJo's family of adopters!

animal.description:
Ferdinand comes to us as an owner surrender and is heart worm positive.  He is beginning treatment for this and will be on restricted activity until the end of April.
Now for the fun stuff!  Ferdinand is a joyous dog.  He loves people.  He is quite boisterous and isn’t the most coordinated fella – hence why we named him after a bull!  He has lived with children in the past, but due to his size and exuberance, older kids are preferred as he can easily knock over smaller kids.  He does well with other dogs, particularly dogs that love to play.  Once he is cleared from heart worm he would love to have someone to play with.  He is still learning about leash manners (he is getting a crash course in this as his activity is currently restricted to leash walks for potty breaks), he is very smart and is learning tricks quickly.
Ferdinand is on medical hold until he completes heart worm treatment

animal.description:
Meet Rosie in Maine!

Rosie has been a bit down on her luck and we are looking to help her turn things around. She had waited a long time to get adopted earlier in the year, and then after a few months in her new home some unfortunate circumstances landed her back in the shelter, so we would really like to help her find a loving forever home for keeps. 

Rosie is a sweet girl with an adorable face and a sharp mind. She is a bit timid at first, but she’ll love you once she knows she can trust you. She would do best in a quieter home where she can settle in and feel safe and comfortable, and a home where she can be the one and only animal would be best. She knows some commands, can be left home alone loose in the house without issue and is an all around wonderful companion who still has some pep in her step. 

Rosie is 6 yrs old and is a healthy and vibrant girl. She has a tendency to get urinary tract infections so she is on a special prescription food that keeps her healthy (C/D Hills Prescription Diet).

We are partnering with the Kennebec Valley Humane Society to find Rosie the perfect forever home and human. If you are interested please fill out our online adoption survey: https://www.olddogsnewdigs.com/adoption-survey/  We are also looking for a foster home for her while she waits for her forever home so if you are interested in fostering Rosie please email us at woof@olddogsnewdigs.com. Otherwise please help us by spreading the word about Rosie so we can turn her luck around. Thanks!!!

PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior pets have a history of being kept up to date on vaccines, annual exams and recommended bloodwork. We also do home checks to make sure that your home environment meets the needs of the particular dog you are interested in.

If you’re interested in adoption, please fill out our online adoption survey at https://www.olddogsnewdigs.com/adoption-survey/

animal.description:
PLEASE TAKE THE TIME TO READ FLETCHER'S BIO.  IT WILL HELP IN FINDING THE RIGHT MATCH FOR HIM.

Fletcher was found hiding under an 18-wheeler out in the country in the freezing rain and is quite lucky a couple found him.  Fletcher is only 11-12 WEEKS OLD.  He weighs 22 pounds,  This means he will likely be a LARGE dog.  With mixed breed dogs we can only guess what their breeds are by looking at shape of the ear, coat, muzzle length, etc.  Fletcher is a big of a puzzle.  We do believe he has yellow lab in him, but his ears are more terrier.  The vet put "terrier mix" on Fletcher's paperwork - partly because of his ears.  You just have to fall in love with him, that's all.

Fletcher needs a family where someone is HOME most of the time.  We are hoping to find someone who has raised a puppy before and has the commitment and ability to work with him on training and socialization.  We want a family that will consider Fletcher a real family member.

Fletch is a typical, curious, high energy, playful pup.  He loves the chase part of "fetch" but doesn't yet want to give it back.  Fletcher does not have any of the behavior characteristics that would indicate any type of abuse and, given a few minutes, will think you are his pal.


FOR MORE INFORMATION PLEASE EMAIL can.adoptions@yahoo.com

animal.description:
Breed:  Formosan Mountain Dog mix
Age:  11 months
Weight:  19 lbs.
Good with dogs:  Yes, another dog in the home is highly desired
Good with cats:  Will Chase
Good with kids: Yes
Energy Level:  Medium High

Available for Adoption:  (Currently accepting applications) 
Your application must be approved prior to meeting any dog.  

Meet Beth.  A vet tech down south found her underneath her deck a few months ago.  We know she had been on the run for a while because she was skinny, covered in fleas and ticks, and practically feral at the time. The vet had to trap her to get her out.  

Once they got her out and to the vet they realized she had a broken front leg which appeared to have been injured for a little while. Back at the clinic, Beth quickly warmed up to the staff.  The vet repaired her leg (see photos of her with her external fixator in place and healed).   Now she loves to run and play!   

During Beth's cat test she did chase after the cat a bit.  We are pretty sure she just was curious and wanted to play, but she will need slow and proper introductions to a feline companion.  When tested with a 12-year-old child she absolutely loved her.  She was a little more standoffish with a younger child but not at all concerningly so.   She would do fine with any age as long as there was proper supervision of interactions. 

Due to Beth's anxiety, she is looking for a home with another dog(s).  In her foster home, she is really making progress by being able to key off of the other dog in the home.

If you would like to be considered to adopt Beth, please complete the adoption application for Beth online here:

http://www.doubledogrescuevolunteers.org/adoption_application.php?dog=Beth

(please reach out to KateS@doubledogrescue.org if you run into any issues with the application process).

For specific questions about Beth, please contact Katherine at KatherineM@doubledogrescue.org.

Mya is settling in nicely and has become playful and affection seeking.  She will paw at her foster mom for pets.

After being there for 6 months our rescue stepped in and she is now relaxing in a foster home. Even though Mya is 13.5 years young she is spunky and a typical chow. She is a typical chow and is independent.  She is deaf and has some vision impairment.  If she startles she may bite out of fear.  We are looking for a chow savvy patient person who will allow Mya to adjust to her new surroundings on her terms.  Please do not say you have chow experience if you do not.  
A physical fenced in yard would be ideal for Mya.

animal.description:
Teddy is an absolutely beautiful and delightful dog.  At approximately 1 yr old, he's full grown at 35 pounds, and we think his regal stature is part Jindo and American Eskimo dog.  He had a rough start in life after being injured by a car.  After two surgeries, he's a bundle of energy and loves to go on walks.  He will be a great running, walking or exercise companion. He is a pleasant playful puppy that will entertain himself at times playing fetch with himself and his beloved toys.  He loves playing with other dogs and even likes pigs but is not great with cats. He would do well in a family with kids over 10 years old because of his previous injuries. He's very smart and obeys many commands and he will walk on water for you if you have a treat or special toy in your pocket.  Please consider adding Teddy to your family, he really deserves a loving home.
 
Our adoption fee covers our dogs being spayed/neutered, microchipped,vaccinations and dewormed. and flea treated. please contact us or go to www.openarmsrescue.org and fill out the online application 760-470-7643

animal.description:
Bonny is a super sweet, loving girl, who was surrendered to us from a hoarding situation. Not animal hoarding, she was an only pet, but her living conditions were horrendous and she had very little space to maneuver. She was ghastly overfed and we've been very successful in getting weight off of her. She's now starting to feel the weight loss and able to move around easier.
No hikes, runs, dog parks, pets, cats, kids or craziness for this girl.
She's 10+ and ready for naps, sunbathing and lazy days.
The perfect fit would be an older female who just wants to give Bonny all her time and love. Bonny can be with men, but does get a little nervous. Certainly nothing that couldn't be overcome with time. She is anxious/nervous around young kids and does need to be an only pet.
If you feel you can give Bonny the best home, please contact us with some info on yourself and your living arrangements/situation.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.German Shepherd dogs, as well as the other herding breeds that we have in rescue, are highly active, energetic, working breeds. They require considerable vetting, exercise, socialization, training, leadership and mental stimuli in order to be well-adjusted, well-balanced, and well-mannered dogs. Even if you exercise and play with your dog daily in your fenced yard, you MUST still take your dog out on daily walks and outings in order to work on his/her leash skills, manners, and social skills. These breeds make great additions to active families who will pamper them, but who will also work with them, as they are smart dogs who need leadership, structure, plenty of activity and mental stimulation. If you are new to German Shepherds (and other herding breeds), please research the breed to make sure this is the dog for you. We ask that you consider the time and financial commitment that your German Shepherd (or other herding breed) dog will require before applying for one. Please review the section on our website (www.heartlandgsrescue.org) 'Is a HUGS Dog Right for You?' for additional information. Estelle is a gorgeous, 30lb girl who is very sweet, but a little shy at first. Estelle was found at an abandoned house that had crumbled to the ground. Underneath concrete and carpet Estelle had built a little nest for her and her five puppies. Lucky for her, rescuers were able to get everyone out safely. Estelle is incredibly sweet and she was immediately grateful and relieved to get to safety with her babies. Estelle and her five puppies have been thriving in their foster home together and are ready for foster to adopt homes of their own. Estelle is a smart German Shepherd mix and it shows in her personality! Although Estelle was found in an abandoned house with her puppies just two short months ago, she has already made a lot of progress from scared, untamed girl to devoted lap dog in that time. Although she's come a long way, Estelle will need a patient, committed adopter as she continues learning how to be a loved, indoor companion. Estelle is shy and quiet at first, but once she feels comfortable in your home, she will want to be physically touching you at all times, and she will use her hound voice if left alone. Estelle is quite the little athlete, and can clear the back of a couch (her favorite way to 'snuggle attack' her foster dad) or a four door fence with ease. Estelle is working on crate training, and at night will voice her displeasure with the crate for awhile before settling down, even though she willing lays in her crate with the door open during the day. Estelle is good with other dogs, and currently lives with two foster sisters and one foster brother, although she needs slow introductions (because of her fearfulness) and is still figuring out what this whole 'play' thing is... Estelle is picky about her toys, preferring a particular ducky stuffed toy she's had since her first foster home, and raw bones - the meatier the better! Pig ears and snouts are also acceptable to Estelle's discerning palate, and she makes quick work of them! Estelle is potty trained, although if you ignore her signs of wanting to go outside, she may have an accident. If you're looking for the perfect oversized lap dog who will be your devoted shadow once she warms up to you, Estelle is the girl for you! The adoption fee for Estelle is $275, all of which goes back into offseting our high-cost vetting expenses and rescuing more dogs. We are a 100% volunteer-run rescue group and rely on adoption fees and donations to continue saving lives. Adoption fees include spay/neuter, current on age-appropriate vaccinations, fecal, deworming, flea/tick and heartworm preventative, heartworm tested if old enough (and treated if positive), and microchipped. Please visit http://heartlandgsrescue.rescuegroups.org/info/adoption for more information about our adoption process and requirements, and to apply. Like any of our dogs, Estelle would make a great addition to an active home that will provide the love, structure, good leadership, activity and mental stimulation that her breed needs. Because of that, Estelle's ideal owners will have prior GSD, or other herding breed experience. Even if you exercise and play with your dog daily in your fenced yard, please remember that you MUST still take your dog out on daily walks and outings, in order to provide sufficient stimulation, ward off boredom, and work on leash skills, and manners. Please review the information in the 'About Us', 'Important Considerations' and 'Adopt' sections on our website menu, as it contains useful information about the breed, adoption fees, the adoption process and our requirements, and how meeting the dogs works.

animal.description:
Blizzard is a 1 year old female Havanese and Poodle Mix rescued from a shelter. She is a high energy girl and needs a family who will invest in training her.

If you think you would be interested, please complete our no obligation application and we can start the process at www.luv4k9s.org. Select Available Dogs then scroll down to application, complete and submit. 

A physical secure fence attached to the residence is a requirement to adopt a dog from our rescue. Invisible fence doesn't meet this requirement. No exceptions.

Our adoption area is primarily OHIO. We will consider KENTUCKY, AND INDIANA AND CERTAIN AREAS OF MICHIGAN, WEST VIRGINIA, AND PENNSYLVANIA if it’s the best fit for the dog.

WE DO NOT SHIP NOR ARRANGE TRANSPORTS.

THE APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED AND SUBMITTED BEFORE WE CAN START THE PROCESS. 

IT CAN TAKE AT LEAST 2 WEEKS TO PROCESS AN APPLICATION SOMETIMES LONGER DEPENDING ON VOLUNTEER AVAILABILITY AND NUMBER OF APPLICATIONS RECEIVED SO PLEASE BE PATIENT. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters must understand that each home is different, and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. 
Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for:
1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (ex. a 4 month old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break) 
2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old, to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise.
3.) Socialization: The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home.
4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded tenfold, for years to come.
Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy. Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time consuming and can be expensive. All Dogs Require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well-trained, well socialized dog is more than worth the effort put in to get them there. 

Our adoption fee includes spay/neuter, routine shots, rabies, worming, microchipped, heartworm testing and they are on monthly preventative. Visit our website www.luv4k9s.org for more information and to complete an application.

animal.description:
Look at this beautiful smooshy face!  Meet London!  London is a ten month old mixed breed pup.  London came to us from another local shelter.  

London is in search of her forever family.  She lived with kiddos (ages 4 to 13) and other pups in her previous home.  She loved to be around the children but was a rough player with the other doggies.  

London has been very sweet with all of the staff and quickly became a volunteer favorite!  She has the biggest wiggly butt we have ever seen!  London loves attention, is great in the car, and loves to play with her toys.  London has a strange habit of chasing shadows and lights.  We are hoping she will out grow this.  London would love a home with a fenced in yard and a family that is home often.  She reportedly was sad to be alone in a previous home and suffered from separation anxiety.  

Please go to our website, www.crcpa.org, and complete an application if you are interested in learning more about Miss London!  If you have the patience for this beautiful baby, we are sure she will repay you with her love.

He was rescued from death row at Miami Dade Animal Shelter by Paws Fur Recovery and is currently being treated like a king in foster with his new foster mom Morgan while we find his new furever home! He absolutely LOVES his hooman companions. He is very low maintenance and enjoys napping his life away as long as he is right by your side. He is ridiculously sweet and is well behaved. Loves rolling around out in the grass in the sunshine. Car rides are his favorite, he will jump in with literally anyone! Fully house trained, no accidents ever. Truly a great dog. Neutered. Vaccinated. Up to date on all shots and prevention. Will you give this dopey guy his new furever home??? How could you say no to that face??? 


PLEASE READ:

animal.description: Hi! My name is Buddha & I'm a very friendly 8-year old male beagle. I'm good with other dogs & cats! My hind legs are paralyzed due to a back injury. I also have a neck injury. I weigh about 30 lbs. My people have to carry me outside & support me while I potty. I bark when I need to go outside. Right now, I'm on "bed rest" until early/mid Feb. After that, I will be neutered. Nittany Beagle Rescue is looking into getting me a cart for after I'm off of bedrest. I can't wait! Also, Nittany Beagle Rescue will be consulting with a veterinarian who specializes in integrative methods to see whether I would benefit from some of their services like acupuncture & an underwater treadmill. I'm a very happy fellow & I'm in a great foster home who can take care of me as long as needed - so no worries there! I like to cuddle next to my person when sleeping on the couch! I need to be crated when I'm in a car - otherwise, I try to move around a lot. I am available for adoption once I'm a little better.

animal.description:
Emmitt is a five year old male boxer or boxer mix. This brindle-coated boy weighs around 45 lbs. Emmitt came into our care after he was surrendered to a local animal control in bad condition. He has been recovering as a foster at All Breed Grooming, Boarding, and Daycare. Emmitt is currently on a prescription food, but it’s made a big difference in his appearance! Emmitt is good with other dogs and probably kids too. His favorite toy is a big stuffed frog. Emmitt is happy to meet new people and that includes you! To adopt Emmitt, apply at ITVrescue.org.

All of our animals are examined by a veterinarian, given age-appropriate vaccinations, dewormed, microchipped, spayed or neutered, heartworm tested and treated if necessary.

Please realize that many of our animals are kept in foster homes. Please complete an adoption application at http://itvrescue.org/adoption-application/ in order to meet with one of our animals. There is no obligation in completing the application, but it helps us find an animal that is most appropriate for your family.  The ITV Rescue Center is open Tuesdays 12-5; Wednesdays 12-7; Thursdays 12-5; Fridays 12-5 and Saturdays 10-5.  The Rescue Center is located at 1417 N. Stockwell Road.  You are welcome to come to our rescue center during open hours to see all of our great adoptable animals. Thank you for your interest in our animals!

NOTE: Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable, so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

animal.description:
Tye Dye won my "Wiggle Butt of the Month" award as she's the wiggliest butt on the East Coast. Happy to meet everyone she meets, her tail wags, and it wags her, and she smiles and is so happy when someone wants to pet her. It's impossible to spend time with Tye dye and not grin an ear to ear grin, as she's so cute, friendly and simply irresistible that she'll turn the grumpiest of faces into a laugh. So cute! Tye Dye's teeth are clean and bright, and she needs some TLC for her mange. Better nutrition and medication under our care is clearing her up. She's all personality, cuddles, fun and love, our Tye Dye. Perhaps named after seeing how bold and bright she is. Nothing (not a little skin issue, or at the moment not having a home) is going to stop our little girl from loving life . There are so many sides to her that she is not a boring dog to be with. There is so much personality packed in this one little 40 pound mangey dog with gentle, soulful, excited and naughty eyes. At one moment, she can be sitting peacefully and tenderly by my side, enjoying caresses, at the other, she literally wiggles...I love that versatility, I love her take on life. Imagine what a companion she would be in your life...She will be the Sun that will brighten your days and nights this winter. Tye Dye needs you and you need her...She's ready to share it all with you, share her kisses and tail wags in exchange for helping her grow up into the fabulous adult dog she's destined to be. She's an awesome pup, ready to wag his way into the future with you and leave the throw away mama dog life behind.

All dogs will be altered, microchipped, and receive age-appropriate vaccines prior to adoption. Please note that the listed location for this dog may not be accurate due to technical limitations of this database and we have transportation options available within 6 hours of NYC (so don't let location hold you back)!

Interested in fostering or adopting? Need more info on this dog? The first step in the process is filling out an application on our website.

animal.description:
*PLEASE READ THE ENTIRE PETFINDER AD.

Davey is an 8 month old, 35 lb cattle dog. Davey was a local owner surrender when it became clear his exercise needs surpassed what they were able to give him. He is a very active guy, even compared to his other Cattle Dog foster siblings!

Davey is friendly with dogs (big and small) who he has a chance to warm up to and who know how to take proper breaks during play. He is good around dog savvy cats but may chase if they are flighty but there’s no aggressive intent. Davey enjoys the company of humans that give him time to warm up to them. He loves HIS humans and will smother them with love. He is wary of strangers but coexists with them just fine, assuming they give him space.

Davey likes playing fetch most of all! He loves off leash hiking on logging roads, using his snuffle mat or other enrichment toys at meal times, training/learning new tricks, parkouring on the furniture, playing with appropriate dog friends, cuddling, and winding down in the evenings with something to chew on. He is a total clown who will make you smile with his antics!
Davey dislikes leisurely leash walks, busy city life, nail trims, sitting still..

Davey has lived with dogs, cats, and kids.
However, Davey would do best in a kid free home so his adoptive family can really work with him during his youth but would do great with kids later in his life when he’s not so rambunctious!

**DUE TO THE HIGH VOLUME OF APPLICATIONS WE RECEIVE, INQUIRIES MADE BELOW THROUGH THE PETFINDER WEBSITE WILL NOT BE SEEN OR RESPONDED TO. IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING DAVEY, PLEASE FILL OUT AN APPLICATION. YOU CAN COPY AND PASTE THE LINK BELOW UNDER "ADOPTION APPLICATION" INTO YOUR WEB BROWSER. 

Davey is neutered, microchipped and has received age-appropriate core vaccines. Davey is being fostered in Mount Vernon and the adoption fee is $330. If you're interested in meeting Davey, please fill out an adoption application on our website: pnwcdr.org/adopt 

Please note: We do not do DNA testing on our foster dogs. The breed description is our best guess based on the dog’s appearance, mother’s appearance, paperwork, etc. 

Adoption Process: 
- Adoption Application
- Phone Convo 
- Meet & Greet 
- Home Visit 
- Application Approval 
- Adoption Fee & Contract 

Adoption Application: 
pnwcdr.org/adopt

Meet Parker 

Name: Parker
Sex: Male (Neutered)
Age: approximately 2 years
Breed: German Shepherd
Location: Tulsa

House & Crate Trained: Yes
Dog Friendly: Yes
Kid Friendly: Unknown
Cat Friendly: Unknown

Parker was surrendered to a vet clinic because he kept getting out and running away from home. He is a very sweet boy who loves affection. Parker would love to find a home with another dog to play with and to show him 'how to dog.' He's mild-mannered and shy, but really feeds off the energy of other dogs and (busy) people. He wants to do things, but oftentimes can't or doesn't know how to instigate. 

Parker needs a home where he will not be left alone outside for any amount of time. It is hoped that his neuter surgery will reduce his desire to roam, but there is no way to know for sure. When in the backyard, he has been caught fiddling with the back gate and looking for other ways to escape.

Parker is a good boy and will make a great dog for an adopter. He's so sweet and pure-of-heart that he whimpers when the squirrels refuse to come down and play with him

animal.description:
MEET VAUGHN!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in it's possession. He is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4516895.

Vaughn was found as a stray and is very fearful of people. He seems nervous of the leash, but once in the play yard did take treats if the handler threw them and ignored him. He would probably do well with some non-punishment based training to help him learn that people are awesome. Because of his behavior with people a dog introduction has not been done, so it's unknown how he reacts to other dogs. Vaughn is still young at only two years old and there's a lot of hope he can overcome his current behavior issues. Suspected to be a german shepherd lab mix he could end up being a great running or hiking partner and may even be a great candidate for dog sports like canine scent work. He just needs an experienced adopter or foster to do some training to help him address his fearful behavior first.

VAUGHN

(MCACC A4516895) may not be available for adoption to the general public, but can be saved by a New Hope Partner, contact the shelter to find out.

To visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show, and we have seen that you can generally show up and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog and the shelter will squeeze you in, except from 12-3PM or closer to the 6PM closing time. (Please know this is not a guarantee). If the dog is at risk, please ask for a supervisor to meet that particular dog.

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. You may also wish to call 602-506-7387 (PETS) and provide the animal's A# above to verify is still available.

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information.

animal.description:
Hi, I am Huck! And not to brag or anything, but I’m a total hunk! I'm a Black and Tan Coonhound, 16 months old and 70lbs. 
Don’t let my large size fool ya, my favorite thing to do is cuddle with my person. I love to sleep in bed with my people and curl up on the couch for movie time! I get along very well with other dogs and kids. I would be an excellent addition to your pack!! I'm house broken, kennel trained and walk on leash like a real pro. I’m also pretty sharp on my basic commands and love to show off my tricks. I love to shake your paw for tasty carrots! 
Basically if we’re being honest, I'm the perfect dog! I’m such a happy and sweet boy. Though I am still a bit of a puppy so I do need exercise too! I hope to meet my forever family soon!

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2020 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

animal.description:
*We do not ship. Adopter must come to Utah to adopt*

Requirements: a calm, mellow home. Adopter must be willing to continue her diet and exercise program. Dogs ok. No cats. Older children or adult only home. 

Gina was rescued off of a local classified page by a Good Samaritan who released her to rescue when they found out this little one needed some extensive dental work. 

Gina is 14 years old and is a miniature poodle. She is extremely obese and her foster family has been working on getting the weight off with weight management food and gentle exercise. Gina has an asymptomatic grade 2 heart murmur which we are hoping will improve once she is back to a proper weight, which for her is probably around 19-20lbs. At her intake she weighed a whopping 37lbs, so she is definitely morbidly obese and needs a home that will continue her weight loss journey. 

Gina is a well mannered, sweet girl who is 100% reliably housetrained, gets along with all other dogs, and loves to be with her people. She doesn’t bark, or chew. Her only naughty habit is that she likes to chase cats. She might do well with cats who are dog savvy, as she isn’t aggressive about it, but she would do best with no kitties in her forever home. While she gets along with other dogs, she prefers her people and would do just fine as an only dog with someone home most of the time. 

Gina has been spayed and had a dental and is up to date on shots and microchipped. She is ready for a retirement home to call her own.

You can find our application on our website or email cavaliercrazyrescue@gmail.com if you’d like to apply to make her part of your family!

animal.description:
NOTE: ONLY SERIOUS INQUIRIES will receive a response.  Read BIO, please!
MEET Calvin!  – When Calvin first joined our rescue, he was skittish and unsure of everything but his foster dad. Now that he’s been with us for a while, he has relaxed and has proven to be quite the sweet heart! His foster family says that he doesn’t know how to play, no matter how often they encourage him to play.  He can still be leery about new experiences, but does need someone who will be patient and let him learn to trust at his own pace.  Calvin is a very active dog, weighing around 75 pounds (give or take a few pounds) and would do great with an active family.  Our ideal adopter would be someone who loves to hike, someone who is able to spend a great deal of time at home with him to provide the attention he needs and deserves.  Calvin loves and does well with other dogs.  He is currently living with two smaller dogs but it would be great if Calvin’s adopter had a canine companion that can show Calvin the ropes.  Based on his reactions on walks, Calvin would do best in a home without cats and his adopter should note that he fixates on squirrels, whether in the yard or on walks;-).  We don’t know how Calvin is with children but are requiring any children in the home be at least 13 years old and are dog savvy.   Calvin is a healthy boy but does need a slow bowl for his meals as he tends to be overenthusiastic about eating, which can cause digestive issues. 

Characteristics: sweet, athletic, lover
Background:  Pulled from overcrowded Texas shelter in July 2020
EMAIL US for an adoption application for Calvin

animal.description:
LACEY!

Lacey is a funny little (short but stout) bundle of awesomeness with an unfortunate history of being surrendered to the shelter by a family unable/willing to give her the time she needed to be a happy, well socialized girl.   We have learned more about Lacey as she has had the fortunate foster family to take the time to empathize, understand and learn what lifestyle she needs to for her to be a well- balanced happy pup.    Lacey will shine brightly in the right home and with an experienced dog owner.  She will need to be in a home with no kids and no cats and plenty of time to continue helping her decompress and build confidence and social skills. 

Lacey has so much love to give and genuinely wants to please.  She enthusiastically embraces any opportunity for a walk or outside adventure, and at 1 1/2 years old, this pup needs some adventures!   Lacey is comfortable in the house and is as happy to snuggle in as she is to adventure out.  Both would be a daily requirement.  She definitely wants to be near her people. She keeps a watchful eye and will relocate her cozy spot as you relocate yours.    Lacey is crate trained but needs to be in a home where she spends most of her time with her trusted humans.  She could easily earn free roam of the home. 

Lacey has shown the ability to greet other dogs and people appropriately when walking on leash, although leash walking is a relatively new experience for her.  She is a quick study and is eager to please, but definitely still needs some guidance.    She also needs direction and support when greeting certain new people as she has a protective, distrustful reaction to some folks.  Time, commitment and positive experiences will help Lacey’s stranger danger diminish and her happy, social side come through.

*Important information - Lacey needs to be loved and appreciated in a calm and gentle environment.  She is a social pup, and loves people, but we have learned that there must have been something in her past that created some confusion and high reactivity when highly aroused.  We learned this the hard way and she now has a bite history after being put in situation she wasn’t ready for.  Lacey is a good dog, with an unfortunate past of people failing her.  She has so much love to offer and we know there is the right person(s) to give Lacey the chance she needs to not only show you how great she really is, but to give her the support she needs to learn how to keep balanced energy.  

We also have set aside some funds to contribute to a private trainer to help Lacey’s journey be a successful one with a committed, loving family. 

This pup is ready to get comfortable and find a place to call home.  Ms. Lacey is about 1 ½ years old and ab out 40 pounds. 

Lacey is being fostered in Williston, VT 
Apply here: http://longtraildogs.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Cotton! You're never too old to look for your furever home, right? I have been around the block ... I'm 15 years old after all. But I still have love to give and I'm ready to settle down!

I'm on the small side (about 18 lbs) and I've actually recently lost some weight the vet told me to lose! I'm a maltese mix and am hypoallergenic. I would prefer to be in a home with adults only.

Some of my favorite things are exploring outside, belly rubs, and naps. I'm very gentle and I'm told I'm very soft. One of my least favorite things is the crate. It's just pretty lonely there. If you let me stay out of the crate in my dog bed, I promise to behave!

What else should you know? Hmm. Well, I am partially blind and I'm deaf. So if your smoke alarm accidentally goes off, I won't get too worried! And even though I'm partially blind, I learn to find my way around pretty well!

I'm very good on the leash and I don't mind other doggies! Sometimes I get so happy to be outside that I even like to do a little jog and will give you a smile. 

I would prefer to be with someone who likes to be home a lot with me - quality time is my primary love language! What's yours? 

If you are interested in me, click Apply for Adoption!

If you're on Adopt-A-Pet or PetFinder, please visit https://www.hopeanimals.org/ to apply!


** Please note that due to COVID-19 and stay at home orders, we are not having our usual adoption events. The first step in the process is to submit an online application. Virtual meet and greets over the phone/computer will be set up before selecting the best fit for adoption. Thank you!

animal.description:
My name is Cole! I’m an 8 year old playful guy. I had a rough past & my family could not take good care of me so they took me to the shelter. Luckily lab rescue got me outta there & set me up in a foster home. I’ve gotten baths to help my skin recover & good food & exercise to get me in great shape for my new home! I love going for walks on a leash but i still need to learn not to pull & bark when I get excited but I will figure it out with practice. 
When I met my foster sister lab I wasn’t sure what to make of her b/c I didn’t learn appropriate doggie manners. I sorta came off like a bully but she is fun to play with and she is teaching me doggie manners. We share toys & get along fine. My foster mom thinks I’ll get along with most dogs but I do like to play wrestle which some doggies might not like. I’d be ok as an only dog though. 
I’m a good boy in the house. I like snoozing on the sofa and LOVE all the toys but I don’t destroy people things. I only want my toys.
I haven’t met cats up close yet but I bet they’d be fun to chase. My foster mom thinks if a cat swiped at me with claws I’d back off pretty quick but I do love chasing things so maybe better without cats. 
I can’t wait to find my forever home. I’m staying in Key Largo & would love to meet you! 


If you are interested in adopting please go to LRRoF.org NOW and fill out an application.

Thanks so much for your interest in our rescue!
Your support, both through adoption and donation is always essential to us and our Labs. Donate today!
We're about matching the right dog with the right family. All applicants will be assigned an Adoption Counselor who will act as their liaison. In addition, a phone interview, home inspection and vet reference (if applicable) are required for eligibility to adopt from Labrador Retriever Rescue of Florida.
